\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2504154 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2504154\charrsid2504154 
Interview conducted 7-8 August 2001, Vice-Chancellor\rquote s Office, Keele University 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid2504154\charrsid8421308 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Could we begin with the year you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
1946.  I was a classic post-War baby, yes!  Yes, yes, yes!  Born and brought up in Liverpool.  My family, I think both sides had been in Liverpool for several generations.  My mother\rquote 
s side for much longer in that area.  And I stayed there until I went to university at 18.  So all my early life was spent in \'85 the northern suburbs of Liverpool, if you like.  My family \'85
 I suppose the thing that immediately strikes me, in talking about issues which might have influenced me subsequently, is that my family was 
really a very female family, actually, and a very kind of happy, fairly large female family - not actually because my immediate family was large, because it wasn\rquote t. \'85 I\rquote ve just got one sister, and she\rquote 
s nearly eight years younger than me, so, really, in childhood, we didn\rquote 
t know each other very well.  So my experience of being a child was more like being a single child, an only child, I think.  And my mother was also an only child. But her family was enormous. Her mother was the eldest of seven children.  T
hey all lived in relatively close proximity, and they had a family grocer\rquote 
s shop, actually, which they still had when I was a child.  So my grandmother and one of her sisters, and one of her brothers, ran the shop, and we lived very close to that, and that
 was very much the centre of family gatherings on a regular basis.  They did actually have a flat over the shop, though we never, we never lived there \'85
 until I was seven, we actually lived with my grandmother, who lived almost next door to the shop.  So it was very much around this \'85 so my maternal family\rquote s grocer\rquote 
s shop, which, itself, was the centre of family distance, and so uncles, aunts and cousins were very important to me in my childhood.  \tab My father\rquote s family was also mostly around Liverpool, and we
 saw them quite regularly.  I think had I not had the very very regular contact with the maternal side, it would have seemed quite regular, but it was definitely less so.  One of my earliest memories is captured, forever, in a photograph which I used as t
he front cover of the book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations and Social Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
, which is a four-generation family picture, with me as a three-year old, and my mother and my grandmother and my great-grandmother, taken as a rather formal picture, in the flat above this grocer\rquote s shop.  It was taken, I\rquote 
m sure it must have been taken because I was the first great-grandchild born to my great-grandmother.  And I believe it was she who had the idea that you\rquote d have four generations of women on this photograph.  But it is a beautif
ul photograph, and I can actually remember the photographer coming and seating us.  I think he must have been a very good photographer, because it is a very lovely picture, with everybody looking very much their own character, if you like.  And though it 
was posed, it doesn\rquote 
t look posed, in that sense.  And that represents not only my earliest, one of my earliest personal memories, but also, I think, very much a touchstone both for my own experiences of family life, and material which, subsequently, has bee
n very important in driving my research programme.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So do you remember that great-grandmother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
She died when I was four, I think, not long after this picture had been taken.  I do remember her, yes.  She did live in the flat over the grocer\rquote s
 shop, and she was still, to a limited extent, actively involved in running the shop when I was a small child.  And I remember that.  I remember she used to bake cakes, which they then sold in the shop - Christmas cakes and things like that.  And I can re
member, as a small child, helping \'85 being allowed to help her to bake the cakes, and that kind of thing.  So I remember, yeah, I do remember her fairly vividly, actually, though I was quite young when she died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And your grandmother, what sort of a person was she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, she \'85
 she was terrific!  And she was a very dominant figure in my childhood, and my sister\rquote s, actually.  She, as I say, she took an active part in running this grocery shop.  She also lived very near to it, and we lived in her hou
se when I was a small child.  \tab When we moved away from there to a new Council estate, when I was seven, and my sister was about to be born, I remained at the primary school which was near to my grandmother\rquote 
s house, so I went to her house every day for lunch, and spent a lot of time with her, and one of her sisters, who also lived with her \endash 
 an unmarried sister.  And then, later in life, when she could no longer manage on her own, and she did manage on her own until she was well into her eighties, she then went and lived with my mother in her house.  So I was, though I\rquote 
d moved away well before that, I saw a lot \'85 throughout her life.  And she lived until she was 96, and she was reasonably physically active, and very mentally alert all the time.  So she was a very \'85 attractive kind of warm person.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I mean, in what sort of way would you say she influenced you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Quite difficult to pin down, because she wasn\rquote t \'85
 she did, to some extent, look after me as a child, in the way in which I\rquote ve described, but I wouldn\rquote t say she was a kind of alternative mother figure really.  She was always definitely my grandmother.  But I think that she \'85 she enjoyed 
\'85 I\rquote ve caught from her the enjoyment of meeting a wide range of people, of doing new things.  She loved doing
 new things, really, until she was very old.  And was very, I think, kind of flexible, more so than a number of people of her generation.  I met the first people of Caribbean origin that I\rquote 
d ever met, through her, because her next door neighbours were a white woman married to somebody who\rquote d been born in Jamaica, I think, actually, because Liverpool, of course, has had a multi-racial community for a very very long time, it\rquote 
s no big deal, in a way, in Liverpool.  But she had these lovely next door neighbours 
who we all adored and, you know, got on well with them and so on.  And so, you know, things like that she was very very open about.  And enjoyment of life, and not any kind of real resentment of anything, you know, that was the sort of person that she was
.  And I guess that I certainly do admire those kind of characteristics, and probably got some of that from her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what happened to the men on your mother\rquote s side, your grandmother\rquote 
s generation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Well, they were around.  All three of them, who were, in fact, my great-uncles, of course \'85 certainly figured in my childhood.  All three of them had been in the First World War.  No, that\rquote 
s not true.  Two of them had been in the First World War, and one o
f them worked for the Civil Service as an Income Tax collector, and had been posted to Dublin, just before the War, and was left there, and he was actually in Dublin in 1918, for the uprisings and so on.  So he had that experience.  But I don\rquote 
t think he ever was sent into the War.  The other two were, and they both sustained some sort of disability as a consequence.  One of them \'85 I think he probably had lost a leg, and had a false leg, but I\rquote 
m not absolutely certain of that, but certainly that sort of disability.  The other one didn\rquote 
t have any apparent physical disabilities, but they always used to speak in hushed tones about how he had suffered shell shock, and he was more than a little bit more than eccentric, it must be said! (LAUGHS)  But this was all t
aken as part of family life.  And they were there, but in the context of family gatherings, it was all very domestic, so the men, including my father, would be there, at least for part of the time, and then they would go off to the pub, or to play bowls, 
o
r something like that, while the women stayed in the house.  Or they would be, you know, put off in one corner and given a cup of tea, while the women really got on with the gossiping and that kind of thing.  So they were never excluded, but it was clear 
that they were very much bit players! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Is that partly because they didn\rquote t run the shop?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
They did, actually.  One of the brothers did run the shop.  And there was, when the shop was sold, there was a real conflict over inheritance, actually, which has become, subsequently, one of the things I\rquote 
ve done research on, with the brother actually taking the vast majority of the profits of the sale, and my grandmother and her sister, who had equally been involved in the running of the shop, were really \'85 probably didn\rquote 
t get their fair share.  My grandmother who was, as I\rquote ve already described, very easy-going, I think took, you know, it sort of passed her by, to some extent.  Her sister was always very unhappy about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about the grandfather on that side?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 He died before I was born.  Yes.  So I never knew him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And then if we look at the earlier generations on your father\rquote s side?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 My father\rquote s mother and father, I can remember, just remember both my father
\rquote s mother and father, my paternal grandparents.  My grandfather on that side, died when I was about six or seven, and he died on the way back from South Africa, where they had been, on a boat, where they had been to visit my father\rquote 
s sister who had emigrated there.  And they had stayed with her for a year, for quite a long time, so I hadn\rquote t seen them for a long time before he died.  And so I can just about remember him.  And I can remember his funeral!  (LAUGHS)  But I don
\rquote t remember very much about him, he clearly wasn\rquote 
t a terribly influential figure to me.  My paternal grandmother, on the other hand, in her widowhood, we did see quite a lot of, and she also lived quite nearby.  She was a much less warm, and a much less sympathetic character tha
n my maternal grandmother, and I was always slightly afraid of her, I think.  But, on the other hand, totally fascinated, because she was out of a certain kind of mould of women of her generation, I think, who were very interested in respectability, and i
n structures of respectability, and particularly in drawing the boundaries around respectability, if you like.  And so I used to absolutely adore going with her.  She played bowls, in a Ladies\rquote 
 Bowling Club, and I used to get taken along when she was lookin
g after me, and, you know, they would play bowls, then they would make tea and so on.  And I used to absolutely love it, because I would sit on the sidelines and hear them all gossiping and doing character assassination on \'85
 on people they knew, who I didn\rquote 
t have the slightest idea who these people were, but it was very fascinating for a young child to sit in and listen to all of this!  So I would say that, probably the main influence that I had from her, was actually unintended, which was an introduction t
o the gradations of the social environment of \'85 what you might call upper working-class/lower middle-class life in Liverpool, at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And you didn\rquote t say what the grandfather on that side actually did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 My grandfather on that side was some kind of artisan, and I\rquote 
ve forgotten what.  He\rquote d retired before I was born.  It was something like joiner, or something of that sort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So did you think of yourself as working-class?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I don\rquote t think, as a child, I wouldn\rquote t have had that langua
ge.  I mean, my educational experience made me acutely aware of social class, which, no doubt, we\rquote ll come on to.  But in my earlier childhood, well, I knew from my paternal grandmother\rquote s side that we defined ourselves as \'93respectable\'94
 and others \'93not respectable\'94.  And from, from the maternal side, the shop was very much the centre \'85 in this small suburb, as it then was, the grocer\rquote 
s shop was very much the centre of the local world, so I knew that we were reasonably important people in the world, but that was about it, really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 What\rquote s the name of that suburb?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Nitherland.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
So could you, perhaps, talk about your parents?  Make a start with your father.  I guess your mother\rquote s going to be more important!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 (LAUGHS) Not entirely, actually!  Not entirely!  Yes, but you\rquote 
re probably right about that!  My father was the eldest of four children, and he, from this family which I \'85 let\rquote s say it was carpentry/joinery, it was something like that, so respectable working-class.  And he was the eldes
t son, and he won a Scholarship to Grammar School \'85 He was born in 1912, so this must have been under \'85
 yes, it was, under the old Scholarship system, where bright working-class children were picked out and so on.  And so he won a Scholarship to the local Grammar School, and went to the local Grammar School, but left at 16, or perhaps it was 15 \'85
 it would have been 15, the school-leaving age, it was always said because he had to go out and earn money to help the family, and that he would have liked to conti
nue further in education.  And certainly, he, himself, always had a very firm belief that he wanted the two daughters to be educated as much as was possible, because I think he, he definitely had a sense of unfulfilled potential for himself.  He, I mean, 
h
e was relatively successful in what he did.  He went off, you know, as a 15 or 16-year old, and went to work for a small company where, I think, he stayed for the whole of his life, and ended up as one of the directors.  And the company was a grain mercha
n
ts.  They had premises on the Dock Road in Liverpool, right by the side of the Docks, and they imported, I think they did import as well, but they certainly exported grain.  So he began as something very junior, and worked his way up through sales and so 
o
n.  But it was a very small company, but, you know, I mean, he clearly was quite good at this job.  And when I was in my childhood, he was, basically, Director of Operations, or something like that, for this company, and it was always a great treat, thoug
h
 slightly frightening, because of the environment, to go and visit him in the office, because he had offices in what was basically a storage mill for grain that was going to be exported.  And so it was a very kind of exotic environment, with rather a dang
erous feel to it, and \'85 and then this sort of rather cosy little office where he spent his time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 You went there quite often, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
No, two or three times a year, as a sort of treat, if you like, that sort of thing.  The owner of this small firm, it was obviously a family-owned firm, and in my childhood, the owner was a woman.  It had been her husband, but he\rquote 
d died and left it to her, so she was actively involved in running the business. She was very kind, and obviously enjoyed \'85 didn\rquote t have any children of her own, I don\rquote 
t think, enjoyed seeing us, and liked us coming to the office, and always invited us out, once or twice a year, to her house: which was, in my eyes, a very grand residence \endash  detached with a garden, and all that sort of thing. 
 So, yes, it was slightly special.  The contact with his work was slightly special.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And as a personality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I \'85
 I think that I found him much more difficult to get close to than I did with any o
f the women in my family, though I think that he was extremely attached to me, probably more than my sister, actually, because I think he probably thought that I would go further in education, which was true, as it turned out!  And so he was \'85
 very supportive, and very keen to support what I was doing, but, I think, slightly bemused at how to treat daughters, really.  So although we lived in \'85
 what now seems to me to be a very small house, in a funny way, he was a kind of distant figure.  He didn\rquote t eat meals with us, except on a Sunday, when it was a family ritual.  Now, that was probably my mother\rquote 
s doing, actually.  And it may have been, now that I look back on it, it may have been something to do with the fact, with economy, you know, that he had the meat and two veg every night, and we probably didn\rquote 
t, you know?  I mean, I never thought that at the time, but I do wonder, now, whether that might have been a part of it.  But, certainly, it seemed to be a very comfortable existence for, you know, mother and 
two daughters to have their little world, and he was slightly - got looked after, and drawn in, from time to time, into this female world, but was slightly on the fringes of it.  I think that\rquote s probably a fair description of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So then what about your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 My mother\rquote 
s still alive.  She was born in 1915, I think, into the sort of family that I\rquote ve described, and she \'85 I don\rquote t know why, I\rquote ve never actually asked her, but she was actually sent to a private school, or what was then a private s
chool \endash  Merchant Taylor\rquote s School for Girls.  And she obviously enjoyed her schooling, didn\rquote t kind of do anything spectacular in academic terms.  I don\rquote 
t think the School, at that stage, necessarily, was as pushy as it was when I went to the same school later, which, no doubt, we\rquote 
ll come on to.  But she, she left school and went and did a secretarial training, and worked as what we would now call a PA, and, I think, was very good at it.  Married my father in 1940, but they didn\rquote t live together until after th
e War was over.  So she was married for six years before I was born, and did give up work, I think, at that stage, but went back to work quite soon after my sister was born.  I think there must have been more financial pressures than I realised, actually,
 at the time.  In fact, I\rquote m sure that was so.  So it was really, so we\rquote re talking now about 1954 or \rquote 
55, a period in which it was very unusual for women with small children to work.  But she did go back into paid work.  She went back into this secretarial j
ob, in a local firm, and got promoted a couple of times, so that she was working, I think she was working for the Managing Director at some stage, at the later stages.  Stayed, more or less, in that job, until she was 60.  So my childhood, and certainly m
y later childhood, was one in which I did have a role model of a mother who went out to work and looked after the family at the same time, and all of that sort of thing.  She was also keen on education, but I think she was a little bit more \'85
 strangely, per
haps, a little bit more sceptical than my father, about how far girls could go, you know, and not quite sure about what it would mean.  I think she was much more conscious of the consequences for a very different lifestyle if her daughters went into educa
tion and did very well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And as a personality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Ja}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8421308\charrsid8421308 net}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 :\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
(LAUGHS) She, she got more relaxed, the older she got, actually!  You know, in my younger childhood, I mean, I think I probably was quite a difficult child, because I think I always was quite wilf
ul, if you like, I had a mind of my own, anyway.  And I think I must have been quite a child to her at some point, and my sister, I know, was much easier.  And so my experience, my memories of childhood, are fairly dominated with falling out with her over
 all sorts of things that you fall out with parents about, and arguing with her about why on earth couldn\rquote t I \'85
 have a duffel coat, I remember, at one stage.  That was regarded as off limits, and that sort of thing.  And it was, my experience was that, as I got older, that she stopped worrying about that sort of thing.  And she\rquote s absolutely great.  And she
\rquote s 85 now, and still extremely lively, goes off and does all sorts of things.  Very independent, very interested in everything that\rquote s going on in the world
 and, you know, a fine example, if you like.  But I think that, as I say, she probably \'85 she probably enjoyed having children maybe less than some people do, I don\rquote t know.  She would never admit that.  And I don\rquote 
t mean anything critical in a way, but I think that she quite likes us now that we\rquote re grown up, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 You were saying you were difficult, I mean, how did they try and discipline you then?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 How did they try and discipline me?  I don\rquote t, I mean, I don\rquote 
t think there was anything standard, particularly!  I mean, I did all the stupid things that you do in childhood, like, you know, reading under the bedclothes and that sort of thing, which they didn\rquote t approve of, disapproved of.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That was against the rules, reading under the bedclothes!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Absolutely, yes!  Yes, indeed.  Yes, that\rquote 
s right!  Yeah!  And then as I got a teenager, all the wanting to stay out stuff and so on.  I think they were, actually, in the end, quite \'85 quite good at getting the balance between freedom and secur
ity right, more or less.  But, but you remember the things, the battles that you didn\rquote t win, I think, don\rquote t you!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Was religion important in the family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, not particularly, actually.  It was sort of part of respectability, but I go
t very involved in a Church Youth Group from the age of about 14 or so onwards, and, and we\rquote ll no doubt come on to this.  But I was very involved in church activities, for some years after that.  But that\rquote 
s not because it came from my family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Did they go to a church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Occasionally.  I think my mother\rquote 
s a more regular churchgoer now than she was then, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Is that Church of England, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Church of England, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about politics?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, Conservative.  Oh, yes, we haven\rquote 
t talked about politics, have we.  My father was a member of the local Conservative Club, but I don\rquote t whether that was a political or a social affair, if you like.  I suspect it was social!  The \'85 atmosphere in which all my family operated was 
\'85 natural support for the Conservative Party.  And, of course, Liverpool, in their \'85 the middle years of the 20}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  century, in their adult life, was really a city in which the Labour Party was really pretty radical, and, regular str
ikes on the Docks and this kind of thing, so that Labour Party politics, in Liverpool, in a family like mine, was associated with that kind of thing, and not with the sort of Fabian \'85 social welfare reform kind of stuff.  So, in some ways it doesn
\rquote t surprise me that they had a natural affinity with the Conservative Party.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
And are there are other things about the family culture, like in terms of leisure, that strike you \endash  music, reading, outings? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 None of those things figure particularly prominently in my childhood.  I don\rquote 
t think the concept of leisure would have been recognised particularly, actually, really.  Not as such, no.  We did things.  My father had a rule that we never went out on Bank Ho
lidays, because the roads were too busy!  So we never went out on Bank Holidays!  He did have a car, and he had a car from quite an early age.  And we always went on holidays in the car, in \'85
 mainly in North Wales or Anglesey, which was a very nice part of childhood, actually. I certainly enjoyed that.  But we didn\rquote t do much \'85 we didn\rquote 
t self-consciously do leisure things as a family together, really.  Occasionally taken to concerts by my grandmother, by my maternal grandmother.  Ditto the theatre, which tended to be sort of popular, well, pantomimes, but fairly popular kind of theatre 
\endash  Gilbert and Sullivan, you know, that sort of thing as well.  And I never went into an art gallery with my family, ever, until I took myself into my first one, you know, in my late teens.  And that\rquote 
s about it, really.  Cinema, we hardly ever went.  I hardly ever went with my parents to the cinema. \'85 I\rquote m not sure that I ever did.  And they, they prevented me from going to the Saturday morning children\rquote s shows, on the grounds tha
t that was not for respectable children, so cinema didn\rquote t figure much in my childhood, really.  So leisure was not \'85 We did go out, we went out in the car.  So on a nice summer\rquote s evening, my father would say, \'93Let\rquote 
s go out in the car.  And we\rquote ll go to \'85\'94 you know, we\rquote d go to Southport or somewhere, and \'85
 later, sit in a pub garden and have a drink, and that sort of thing.  Lots of outings with the women in the family, you know, combinations of my mother, my grandmother, her sister, outings to Liverpool or to Southport, to visit the shops, to go to a caf
\'e9, all that kind of thing, very much prominent in my childhood, but I don\rquote t think it would have been thought of as leisure.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Fine.  Well, shall we perhaps pass on to school, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Okay.  Well, I \'85 one thing that I\rquote 
ll say at the beginning, and come back to is, apart from, I think, the first 18 months of my schooling, I was educated entirely in female-only establishments, which is probably quite unusual.  But my schooling began, not terribly success
fully, at a small private, what you can only call a \'93Dame School\'94, I think, in a big old house nearby, which was not terrifically successful, actually.  But I did go there until I was seven.  I don\rquote t know what I learned really, but I \'85
 (LAUGHS), but I then went to the local primary school.  And the local primary school was both boys and girls, but they were segregated, so it was girls downstairs, boys upstairs, and the playgrounds were separate, and so on.  So I was in the girls
\rquote  part of the school.  And I don\rquote t, I don\rquote t remember enjoying that very much, actually, and I didn\rquote 
t enjoy it very much because it turned out, quite quickly, that I seemed to be better than most of the other girls, at most things.  And it was one of those schools where your position in the classroom was according to how you\rquote 
d done in the latest tests \'85 so I was always sitting in \'85 two or three desks at the corner of the classroom, where all the people who had done best, sat.  And I found that a really pretty uncomfortable experience fo
r most of my primary schooling, because I was always being picked out as being clever, being able to do things, and you, therefore, get backlash from the other children!  (LAUGHS)  And I wouldn\rquote t say I was unhappy, but I don\rquote 
t think it was a terribly stimulating environment. \'85 I never remember doing anything exciting, you know, we didn\rquote t learn to swim, we didn\rquote 
t get taken on outings, as I recall, that kind of thing.  And I was pretty glad to escape from it really.  But I escaped into a completely different 
sort of environment which, you know, which, I think, had been very important in my life.  But, you know, it was a transition that was a bit difficult, because I went to Merchant Taylor\rquote 
s School, which was, at that stage, a Direct Grant Grammar School, so 25 per cent of the places were reserved for people coming on Local Authority Scholarships, so you had to sit an examination. \'85
 I sat the 11+ examination, which I passed, of course, and also this Scholarship Examination for Merchant Taylor\rquote s.  And the primary school that I went to had almost no experience of this.  They didn\rquote 
t get very many people into the Grammar School, and I don\rquote t think they\rquote d ever sent anybody to Merchant Taylor\rquote s before.  And it must have been because my mother had been there that, you k
now, that my family had some notion that this was a good idea.  But for some reason, that astonishes me now, the primary school decided to put me in for this Scholarship a year early, so I was ten when I sat it, and ten when I sat the 11+ for that matter,
 and I passed and got in, at the age of ten.  So I went, I went to this Direct Grant Girls\rquote  Grammar School, on a Scholarship, a year younger than all my classmates, in an area \'85 it\rquote 
s in a rather more wealthy part of Liverpool than I was brought up in, so in
 an environment where almost everybody else came from families which were much better off than mine.  And it was altogether, I mean, a kind of amazing thing to do to a young child, really.  But I flourished, I think, as a consequence of it!  You know, I m
ean, in a sense, it was the high risk strategy which, in the end, probably did pay off.  But \'85 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
You said they had a `strategy.  Did you really feel they had a conscious strategy for their children, your parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  Did I say that?  That probably is overstating it, actually.  That\rquote 
s probably overstating it \'85 though I think they were \'85 they were both very clear, particularly my father, that a good education was what was needed.  And the fact that they had daughters didn\rquote t make any difference t
o that, you know, it was still what was needed.  And I think my father did have something close to a strategy, quite apart from the fact that, you know, he did, very explicitly, want his children to have opportunities that he would have liked to have hims
elf, but didn\rquote t.  He actually had a strategy for daughters.  I can remember this quite vividly, because at some point in, much later in my life, I think when I was at university, and wondering what to do afterwards \'85
 I remember having several conversations 
with him, in which he was very firm on the point that I must get a job, and ideally, I must get myself professionally qualified.  And the reason for that was that, even though I thought I was going to get married, which I did quite soon after leaving univ
ersity, you would never know, in your mid-thirties, you might be left on your own, and you then needed something to be able to look after yourself, you know, some means of properly looking after yourself.  And I remember saying to him, \'93Oh, Dad, don
\rquote t be ridiculous!\'94  But actually, that is precisely what did happen!  Well, not precisely, but it was close enough to make me remember what he\rquote 
d said.  And so he did actually have, he had a strategy, he wanted his daughters to be independent.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That\rquote s interes
ting.  But neither your mother, nor your father, had any openly feminist ideas?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, I don\rquote t think so.  Not that I could recognise as such, though I don\rquote 
t think that either of them \'85 they both were probably at the \'85 towards the end of the spectrum i
n which they thought that women were quite capable to do anything they wanted, and why should you worry about it, sort of thing.  I never felt, with either of them, that because I was a woman, my life was going to be restricted to certain sorts of activit
ies, actually.  I wouldn\rquote t call it explicitly Feminist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Would you see that as partly as having been empowered by having the shop, and working in the shop, rather than by any particular ideas?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  I think, yeah, I think \'85
 for my mother, it would be a consequence of the sort of family she had, in which women did do quite a lot.  And for my father, maybe a little bit more thought through, actually.  Maybe a little bit more thought through than that.  Mmm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Anyway, we were at the school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
At the school.  Oh yes, I think I was sort of explaining how I was thrown in at the deep end.  I was very much thrown in at the deep end, and it could have, I mean, it could have all turned out very badly, I think, given the diff
erence between my background and most of the others, the difference in age, the geography of it all and so on.  But, anyway, it didn\rquote t work out badly.  And I loved the \'85
 the educational part of it.  You know, I mean, that was where, you know, I got introdu
ced to literature and art and music and so on, and very much responded to all that.  Less so to the sciences.  I suspect that the sciences were not as well-taught, anyway, because in girls\rquote  schools, at that stage, they were not really \'85
 geared up for it in
 quite the same way that they subsequently became.  So I very much responded to that.  I did, however, find the social aspects of it very much more difficult to cope with, and I think that did really quite influence me in a number of ways, eventually maki
n
g me somewhat politically more radical than I might otherwise have been, I think, about that sort of thing. Because I knew that my parents were doing the best for me that they could, and they were always very happy for me to bring school friends home, but
 they couldn\rquote t offer what \'85
 my friends could offer when I went to their houses, you know, staying in a bedroom of your own, and all that sort of thing!  And so, of course, I spent quite a lot of my teenage years being semi-embarrassed about my background, b
ut knowing that that was wrong, and coming to terms with all of that \'85 And I don\rquote t think the School helped particularly there, I have to say.  I\rquote m not aware of any sort of sensitivity to that kind of issue.  And I wasn\rquote 
t the only person who\rquote d come from that sort of background, though there weren\rquote t very many of us.  And the one thing which they did do, which I\rquote ve always deeply resented, was take my Liverpool accent away.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 The School did?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Mmm.  Mmm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Because you were teased about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, no, it was nothing to do with that.  It was, it was the School\rquote 
s policy, if you \'85 The small number of us who had got into the School, with a Liverpool accent, had to stay back for elocution lessons after school.  And, you know, at the age of ten, when you know you\rquote re in an environment that you don\rquote 
t belong, you\rquote ve got a huge incentive to go along with this.  And so I lost my Liverpool accent, and I never got it back again.  Well, I have traces of it, actually, but I never got it back again.  And I re
gard it with some sort of mild amusement now, but in my twenties, I became to really quite resent that.  I felt as if some real aspect of my identity had been taken away, actually, and denied.  I don\rquote 
t feel that any more, but I did then.  I did then, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Was there any ridiculing of the Scholarship girls?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Not really, no.  And I think that was because, when I went to the school, as opposed to 30 years earlier when my mother had gone, when, I suspect, it might have been a slightly differen
t sort of environment, by the time I got there in 1956, it was a very academic school, and it was very much geared to getting as many girls as possible into the best universities, as it were.  And so the Scholarship girls were rather precious, because the
y\rquote d all been selected for academic ability, whereas the 75 per cent who were fee-paying, they \'85
 they did go through some sort of selection process with them, but, in the end, they had to fill the places, and they also had to keep on good terms with influent
ial circles in the locality.  And so it was very clear that there was actually quite a wide range of academic ability there, and that some, I mean, some girls left at 16 with very, very few \lquote O\rquote 
 levels, if any.  But the School, and the staff of the School, were geared up to the academic agenda, and so we were actually rather well looked after, in some ways, by the School.  It was clear that we were valued.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
And did changing your accent affect your relationship with your family, or the neighbourhood?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1773805 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I was not, in any way, aware of it changing my relationship with my family, no.  I mean, they used to tease me a bit sometimes, because I think that they\rquote 
d got used to the idea of having a rather sort of \'93clever\'94, if you like, put it that way, clever girl in the family, from quite an early age, actually.  So I would be occasionally teased about being clever, but not in an unpleasant way.  And I don
\rquote t think the \'85 I\rquote m not aware of the accent being an issue.  In terms of the locality, I don\rquote t know whethe
r it was the accent so much as the fact that I had an enormous amount of homework, and I was pretty conscientious about doing it.  So from the time when I went to that school, a lot of my times at evenings, and sometimes at weekends, were taken up doing h
omework.  So I certainly did, I mean, I wasn\rquote t in the same kind of friendship circles as I had been when I was at primary school, to the same extent.  But I think it was probably as much, it was as much the homework commitment \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1773805   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Particular teachers?  The ones that I remember particularly, were actually, became important when I was in the sixth form. \'85
 Miss Stone and Miss White, they lived together.  I assume they were a couple, but I don\rquote t \'85 I mean, they never declared that, as it were.  I think we would ha
ve been amazed if they did!  I mean, we used to talk about it!  (LAUGHS)  But Miss Stone was Head of English, and Miss White was Head of Art.  And it was quite a \'93Miss Jean Brodie\'94
 set-up, actually.  They used to spend all their holidays in Italy, and they very much liked having a certain group of sixth form girls who they \'85 By the time you got to the sixth form, you were very much picked out as \'93this is the clever group\'94
, you know, and I was one of those, and I guess there were probably about ten of us, or
 something, who were cultivated, particularly, by these two teachers.  And it was great!  You know, I mean, I remember eating pasta for the first time, in their house, and thinking it was amazing that anybody ate any food like that, you know, pasta and sa
lad or something, you know!  And I thought this was astonishing.  I hadn\rquote 
t been introduced to anything like that before.  And that sort of thing.  And they, I mean, they organised sort of informal visits to art galleries and that sort of thing, which was \'85 
great, actually, and treated you very much as young intellectuals that they were trying to bring on, kind of thing!  (LAUGHS)  But before the sixth form, I don\rquote t remember anybody particularly influential.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what subjects were you specialising in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, art subjects \endash  English, French and German, which I failed at \lquote A
\rquote  level.  A terrible German teacher!  Actually, I didn\rquote t have an aptitude for languages at all!  I don\rquote t know why I did it!  But I did, anyway.  But English, French and German, yes, I did at \lquote A\rquote  level, yes.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So then what happened after you left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, I went, I had a year, what we\rquote d now call a \'93gap year\'94
, and then after that I went to Bedford College, in London University, to read sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what were you doing in this year off?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, I probably actually should tell you about \'85
 about the process of getting to Bedford College, before we get to that, actually, because that\rquote s \'85 that is quite interesting, in a way.  I think I said befor
e, the School was very focused on getting its girls into the best universities, and that meant as many as possible into Oxford and Cambridge, quite apart from anything else, and this little group that I was in, were all destined to go to Oxford and Cambri
dge.  And for reasons that I can\rquote 
t entirely explain, even now, that have got something to do with the Church Youth Group that I was involved in, and developing a kind of social conscience, and developing some sort of political interest as well, I decided I 
wanted to do sociology.  Now, this was 1963, and there wasn\rquote t much sociology around then.  But I\rquote d got it in my head that I wanted to do it. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 How had you heard about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I must have \'85 I can\rquote t remember how I\rquote 
d heard about it.  I think I had some notion of possibly wanting to go into social work, and thinking that it was relevant to that.  But I don\rquote t know how I\rquote 
d heard about sociology, certainly not from the School.  And I remember getting really quite fixed on this.  And, of course in those days, neither Oxford nor Cambridge offered sociology.  So I decided, I wasn\rquote 
t going to go to Oxford or Cambridge, I was going to somewhere where I could do sociology.  And this was deeply offensive to the School, and they tried, did their best to persuade m
e to do English at Oxford, and assured me that I was bound to get in and so on, but I wouldn\rquote 
t have any of it.  And in the end, I had to go and be interviewed by the Head, who said to me that it was, you know, it was a very wayward thing to want to do, and she was really very displeased with me.  But if I absolutely insisted, as she\rquote 
d understood from other teachers, I was doing, then she did know that you could sociology at London University.  And so that\rquote s what she would recommend.  But, under no circumsta
nces, would the School give me a reference for the London School of Economics, because that was too Left-wing!  (LAUGHS)  And so she\rquote 
d been doing some other investigations, and she had discovered that Bedford College, which was a very respectable institution, where they had sent other girls, which, of course, was a women\rquote 
s college at that stage, offered sociology.  And so if I insisted on pursuing this, they would, in fact, give me a reference for Bedford College, if I so wished.  And so that\rquote s where I ende
d up.  And I did apply to a lot of other universities as well, I think I got places at most of them, but Bedford was my first choice, and that\rquote s where I went.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So you decided to defer for a year.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1773805 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 But I deferred for a year.  I was only, I went through the whole of my schooling a year younger than everybody else, so I was 17 when I finished my \lquote A\rquote  levels, and it altogether felt \'85
 well, first of all, quite a few people were staying on for a third year in the sixth form, to do entrance examinations.  I had to do an entrance examination for Bedford as well, which I could have done in the second year sixth, but chose \'85 it wasn
\rquote t that unusual to take a third year, chose not to, and decided that \'85 I thought it would be a good idea, if I might want to go into social work, to do something else before I went to university. \'85
 So I did. I spent the year as an unqualified teacher, which you could be in those days, in an extremely tough primary school, infants school, in Kirby, which is \'85 I don\rquote t know if you k
now, Kirby is one of the overspill estates, which was built post-War, the post-War redevelopment of Liverpool.  It had an extremely tough reputation then, and it certainly does now.  And I spent a year, as a teaching assistant, if you like, in this infant
s
 school, five and six year olds.  And it really, really was very good for me, actually, because I learned a little bit about the process of education from the other side, if you like, in, really, a pretty hostile environment.  I also learnt an enormous am
ount about the social problems created by those post-War estates, and about the sorts of lives that some children, the sort of impoverishment that some, in every sense, that some children were living in the city in which I\rquote 
d been brought up.  So it was a very good thing to have done, and I think it was probably quite a maturing experience as well.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And you lived there, or you stayed at home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
No, I travelled daily.  I travelled daily.  One of the teachers lived not too far away from where I lived, so I think I travelled with her, if I remember rightly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And did you get close to any of those teachers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Not particularly, no.  Not particularly.  I think I was just a useful addition.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Now, was this all sort of related to the Church Group that you mentioned earlier?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I think, I think the desire to do something like that, which has a slightly sort of 
\'93good works\'94 feel about it, probably was.  Yes, that\rquote s right.  The Church Group that I was associated with was \'85
 the Church was quite a sort of socially enlightened kind of church, and it was, a lot of it was about, you know, opening my eyes to understanding Third World issues, as well as issues of poverty in Britain, and that kind of thing.  And, yes, there is def
initely a connection there, at that time in my youth, if you like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And how long did that enthusiasm carry on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, I think that\rquote 
s quite a difficult question to answer, actually, because on one level I could say permanently, because I think I\rquote 
ve never lost a number of the kind of social agenda issues, and political agenda issues, that I began to be interested in at that time.  Another influence, actually, was CND.  One of my school friend\rquote 
s families was very heavily involved in CND.  She was a bit unusual, as well, with me, in a different way, and so I got involved on the fringes of CND as well.  But \'85
 I think my kind of own commitments, if you like, in the social and political sense, were probably formed at that time, and the influence of this
, the Christian influence, has some indirect relevance to that, I think.  As to involvement in the Church, as such, well, that\rquote 
s a different story, because, as you probably know, I did ultimately marry somebody who was a clergyman in the Church of England,
 and was married to him for 11 years.  So that, my involvement in the Church, obviously, was geared to that particular experience then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So was this like Christian Socialist, in a sense?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid8421308\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I don\rquote t think that\rquote 
s a term that I would have recognised then, because nobody introduced me to it.  But it\rquote 
s not too far from the mark.  I think the social gospel was one that was current in the sixties, which would have been a more familiar one.  But, yes, essentially yes.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Okay.  So then you went to Bedford.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Would you like to talk about some of the people there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  I mean, that\rquote 
s coming much closer to my present interests.  I thoroughly enjoyed my education in sociology, as an unde
rgraduate.  And it was only afterwards that I realised that it was, probably even when I had it, rather out of date!  But it was quite, it was quite policy oriented, actually.  Well, it was a mixture, really, of a policy orientation and \'85
 quite theoretical stuff.  But the theoretical stuff was a little bit kind of incoherent, it was a mixture, a mixture of different traditions, and I don\rquote 
t remember anybody quite explaining where these different traditions came from.  So we did a bit of Parsons and Structura
l Functionalism, and we then did some very fascinating comparative sociology, which I now, I now know, probably was Weberian, but I don\rquote 
t think anybody really explained that! (LAUGHS)  And then we did quite a lot of sort of community, family welfare type issues, criminology, and a good methodology training in quantitative methods.  And so that, I mean, it\rquote s not too long since I
\rquote ve seen some of the people who taught me, actually.  The person in charge of the Department at Bedford, when I was there, was Oliver McGregor, \'85
 whose interests in sociology, very much shaped the curriculum, I think.  And actually, have really shaped my interests to quite a remarkable extent, when I think about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  Can you be more specific about his interests? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, he \'85 he went on to \'85
 after I graduated, to chair the Royal Commission on Single Parents, and was, subsequently, actually involved in the Press Complaints Commission, but that was something different.  But his interests were very much in family and, family m
arriages, not so much kinship, actually \endash 
 marriage, family, children - from a mixture of a sociological analysis and a social welfare perspective.  And was, I think was really quite a central figure in developing a sociological approach to those issues, fr
om that sort of perspective, in this country. Because we didn\rquote t do too much American stuff, you know, of which there was an awful lot at that stage.  It was quite radical.  And he was quite influenced by Feminism, first wave Feminism.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Really?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Late 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\super\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
 century Feminism.  So the way he taught about families had a very strong gender perspective in it.  You know, we did Josephine Butler and the Contagious Diseases Act, we did all these sorts of things, and were part of the course in Family Manag
ement or whatever it was called, that he taught, as well as the more overt policy issues around Beveridge and all of that kind of thing.  So I learnt from him a sociology of marriage, family, children, which had a very strong gender component to it, and a
 strong historical sense as well, and I think that some of these things have very much shaped my interests.  And I was quite astonished when, when, five years ago \'85
no, six years ago, when I came here, and I was clearing out my office in Lancaster, I threw away a lot of things then, one of which was, I\rquote d been carrying around with me, for all that time, the copies of the examination papers that I\rquote 
d sat in my Finals, and I was amazed to see that some of the questions that I\rquote d actually answered in those were really quite close to my then interests, and, I mean, by then I\rquote d become somebody who\rquote 
d done, made quite a significant contribution to work on families myself.  And yet \'85 yet the, and obviously done it in a different way and so on, but, but the issues were not that different.  So, so that\rquote 
s why I think this particular, the way that McGregor taught, was very influential, even though I found him a rather \'85 difficult man, I think.  He was \'85 I think he, he probably, he probably wasn\rquote t that good at dealing with wom
en, actually, paradoxically!  He was interested in gender, he taught in a women\rquote s college but, you know, it was dealing with young women, he didn\rquote 
t quite know how to do it!  The role model for young women was Bernice Martin, who must have really been quite young when she taught us.  But she was brilliant, and she was much more theoretically inclined.  And I\rquote 
ve seen her relatively recently, actually, and kept in touch with her in various ways.  Criminology, which I enjoyed very much, though, again, taught by somebody who probably didn\rquote 
t know how to deal with young women, that was taught by Louis Blom-Cooper, who, I think, just had a part-time position in the College.  And I\rquote ve seen him quite recently as well.   And that was very much up to the minute. Basical
ly, he comes up to it from a socio-legal perspective, and so, and that was a bit different.  But it was pretty good, actually, pretty good stuff.  The only problem was that the examination paper that we sat bore very little relationship to what he\rquote 
d taught! (LAUGHS)  But you learn to live with that!  So I think those are probably the most \'85 the most prominent people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about new friends there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yeah, I did make friends with a number of people there.  I\rquote 
m not very closely in touch with many of them, except those that I still come across in a professional capacity.  So one who I now see very regularly, is Karen Dunnell, who\rquote 
s currently in a very senior position in the Social Statistics Section of the Office of National Statistics, and she and I were students together.  And I\rquote 
m a non-executive on the Policy Board of ONS, so we actually meet, in a professional capacity, quite frequently.  And there were one or two others like that.  But, on the whole, the people I \'85
 made friends with, went off and did different sorts of things from me, if you like, and I haven\rquote t really kept up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So none of them were an important influence, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I don\rquote t think so, no.  No.  I wouldn\rquote t say that, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And out of that group, did many go on to sociology as a career?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  I\rquote 
m not aware of anybody, apart from Karen, who more or less did.  No.  Don\rquote t think so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And did you have contact with LSE?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Yes, we had a number of lectures, there wer
e a number of shared lectures between Bedford and LSE, and they were the only two Colleges in London University that offered sociology at that time, I think.  So, yes, there were a number of lectures.  Yes, we went to seminars at the LSE.  My headmistress
 would have been horrified to know that!  But, there we are!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So that wasn\rquote t important to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
I remember going to lectures given by Terry Morris, on criminology, actually, which I rather enjoyed, but I don\rquote t remember anybody else, particularly, from LSE, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Not even Titmuss?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  I don\rquote t think Titmuss taught, I don\rquote 
t remember being taught by Titmuss, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what happens next?  We\rquote ve got to 1967.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Right.  What happened next?  Well, I didn\rquote t have a plan \endash  I\rquote 
ve never had much of a plan, actually!  Truly!  And I, I did actually feel, and I think I was probably right to feel that, that the one thing I knew was that I didn\rquote t want to stay in a university environment, or to continue to a further level
 of education.  I felt as if I\rquote d spent all my life being educated.  And, in a way, I think had, because, you know, the school that I went to, \'85 you know, we worked pretty hard.  And at university, I did \'85
 really lots of good things, and my cultural interests expanded quite significantly, but I still did work pretty hard.  So I, the one thing that I didn\rquote t want to do was to continue with post-graduate work, but I didn\rquote 
t really know what I did want to do.  I knew that I was probably going to get married fairly soon after that, so location was an issue.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 You\rquote d already met your future husband?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yeah. \'85 I\rquote 
d known him for a very long time, he was in the same Youth Club in Liverpool, that I belonged to.  We were part of the same kind of \'85
 social awareness being raised at the same time, so to speak.  He went to university in Hull, but we kept in close contact while we were both at university.  And so I didn\rquote 
t really know what I wanted to do.  I did know that I needed to be somewhere near Cambridge, which was where he was going to be, and so I applied for, and got, a teaching post in a girls\rquote  secondary modern school, which was in Bishop\rquote 
s Stortford.  Girls\rquote  secondary modern in Bishop\rquote s Stortford.  And I started there, I think I started there 
in the autumn after I graduated.  In the interim, London University then, and possibly still now, takes much longer than anywhere else to get its degree results out, and so although all my friends who had gone off to other universities had theirs in early
 July, I think it was the middle of August when a letter popped through the letter box, to tell me that I\rquote d got a First, and it \'85
 it was really one of the most traumatic experiences of my whole life, because nobody, but nobody, had prepared me for the possi
bility that I might get a First.  I do remember, conversely, I remember McGregor giving us a little pep talk in our final year, saying, you know, \'93We want you to all do well\'94, and so on, \'93And this is how we \'85 we must work hard, but really, don
\rquote t expect that anybody\rquote s going to get a First, because the last time anybody got a First in sociology from Bedford College was ten years ago\'94, or something like that.  So, whether this was true or not, I don\rquote t know.  And so, and I 
\'85 was not one of those \'85 I mean, there
 were some of my friends who were sort of aiming for a 2:1 kind of thing, and I think that I just thought, probably because I was the first generation in my family to go to university, that a degree was good enough, you know, I didn\rquote 
t really mind very much.  So it was a tremendous shock to be told that I\rquote d got a First.  It really disrupted my sense of myself and so on.  It was difficult for a whole range of reasons.  I think one of my friends, who\rquote 
d gone toYork, got a First in English, but nobody else had.  And it was a very strange experience.  And then, you know, a few days later, another letter appeared from Oliver McGregor, offering me an SSRC Studentship, saying, \'93Now that you\rquote 
ve got First Class, we have this to give, and would you like to have it?\'94  And I wrote back saying, \'93Well, no thank you very much.  I\rquote ve decided I want to do something else.  I\rquote ve got a teaching position\'94.  And, actually, I hadn
\rquote t got the remotest idea what I was being offered, and what it meant to say no to it, actually!  (LAUGHS)  But, anyway, that\rquote s what I did, and so I went off and taught in this girls\rquote 
 secondary modern school.  Quite enjoyed it.  They were just beginning to teach \lquote O\rquote  level sociology, so I introduced \lquote O\rquote  level sociology at this school, and my pupils all did very
 well, and it was okay.  It was a slightly eccentric sort of place.  I quite enjoyed it.  But it was quite a long distance to travel by train, or by car, from Cambridge, and we\rquote d settled into Cambridge, I\rquote 
d got married and settled down in Cambridge by then.  My then husband went into theological training in Cambridge, trained for the ministry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 He was  Geoffrey Spedding? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That\rquote 
s right, yes.  Correct, yes.  And so I, after about 18 months, I got rather fed up of travelling, and wondered what th
e options were, and saw a research post advertised, research assistant type post, advertised in the Department of Anthropology, in Cambridge, and applied for it, thinking it would be more convenient, you know, to be working in Cambridge.  And it was a pos
ition being advertised by Jack Goody, who was a very grand figure in Cambridge anthropology, I subsequently discovered.  And he interviewed me, and \'85 he didn\rquote t appoint me, he\rquote d obviously already got somebody in mind for this, but he said 
\'85 well, he was bearing in mind my interest in all of this, And very soon afterwards, contacted me again - or maybe it was Esther who contacted me - and just offered me a position of a research assistant, working on Esther Goody\rquote 
s project of fostering children in West Africa.
  And so I went to Cambridge, Department of Anthropology, worked as a research assistant in the Centre for African Studies, and it was a wonderful experience.  I mean, the work was a bit boring, actually, because I was analysing her data, if you like, and
 it was the early days of putting your data on to computer, so I would have to cycle down to the University computer, every morning, and find what print-outs we\rquote 
d got overnight.  I think I even had to learn to do some programming, in those days, in order to get the print-outs and so on.  But it was such a totally different experience of what being in a university means, when you\rquote 
re not a student, and of being in a university as part of a \'85 set of research activities.  I loved it.  I got on very well with Esther.  I went along to seminars, you know, and heard all sorts of really interesting people. \'85
 I learned, I think, I may have a slightly rosy view of this, but I think, from going to seminars in anthropology, in Cambridge at that time, I learnt, for the fir
st time, what a real kind of scholarly community is like, if you like, which was for the very tough-minded intellectual debate - which I enjoyed, even though I didn\rquote t understand most of what they were talking about, because I hadn\rquote 
t had a training in anthropology - but also, a kind of respect for people\rquote 
s ideas, whoever they were, you know.  So the research students would pipe up, and people would be interested in what they said, if they said something sensible.  If they didn\rquote t say something sensible, they got demolished!  But, \'85
 I thoroughly enjoyed that.  I really did.  And that was what tempted me back into academic life, really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 How would you describe Esther as a person?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I think she was Jack\rquote s second wife, she was much younger than him.  And \'85
 I think she was an extremely good anthropologist, anthropological researcher.  She also did a lot of teaching.  And I think she was very good with students, and that\rquote 
s why she was good with me as well.  I mean, she was very clear that she was training me up for a possible research career, and she was very good at that.  I got on with her very well.  She was intellectually generous, actually, in all sorts of ways, and 
\'85 didn\rquote t seem fazed by the fact that I was not an anthropologist, didn\rquote t \'85 you know, told me what I needed to know when I didn\rquote t know things, without it being a big issue.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And Jack, did you have much contact with him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yeah, quite a lot, actually.  Quite a lot.  He, I mean, he was then the very, very grand figure within anthropology, \'85
 and acted that a little bit, you know, had loads of people running round after him, and... in the Centre for African Studies in Cambridge, which was his sort of patch, if you like, there were an enormous number of research students, African resea
rch students, and members of staff from African universities.  I remember it was a period when Amin was just at the height of his awfulness in Uganda, and we had a number of people from Makerere at that stage, which was, I think was an extremely good univ
ersity before he closed it.  And so very much aware of the politics of Africa at that point, but they all came to work with Jack. \'85
 But he was not a remote figure, you know, because I used to go round to their house and so on, and he was perfectly good company, actually, you know, in those sort of social circumstances.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Do you think you picked up intellectual ideas from anthropology?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I was very attracted to the anthropological method, and I think \'85
probably it was more methodological than anything else. \'85 It very much drew you in the direction of \'85 I\rquote d never been exposed to fieldwork methodology before, and I learned it\rquote s strengths.  Perhaps I didn\rquote 
t learn too much about its weaknesses, but I certainly learnt its strengths there.  I probably got a basic grounding in anthropological work on kinship as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And did that seem to be different from what you\rquote d got from McGregor then? 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Completely.  But because it was anthropology, at that stage I didn\rquote 
t realise the significance of the difference, if you like, I just thought it was a different discipline.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Can you go on to say more about this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Not particularly, because I think \'85 I didn\rquote t get a perspective on what I
\rquote d learned as an undergraduate, until I moved on to my post-graduate work at Bradford.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Right.  Okay.  So, well, how does the next stage happen, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I left Cambridge when my husband was ordained, and went into his first job a
s a minister of the Church of England, which was in Bradford.  He was on the staff of Bradford Cathedral, for his first post.  So we moved to Bradford, and I had to decide what I was going to do.  And I remember Esther saying to me, \'93
Bradford?  I think they might have a university in Bradford.  Let\rquote s see \'85 let\rquote s see whether they do sociology\'94.  So we looked it up, and they did, indeed, have a university, and they did, indeed, do sociology.  \tab 
So I wrote a letter to say \'85 I had been tempted to the idea that doing research was something that I would enjoy, and she persuaded me that the next stage was, in fact, not to go and apply for another job on somebody else\rquote 
s research project, but to do my own Ph.D..  She was definitely responsible for that.  I think I would, otherwise, if I\rquote 
d have stayed at all I would have gone, you know, applying for research assistantships.  So I then wrote to the Head of the Bradford Sociology Department, who was John Eldridge at that time, and said, you know, \'93Any chance of signing on for a Ph.D.?
\'94  And got interviewed, and offered a Studentship.  So the second time, I didn\rquote t say no!  (LAUGHS)  So I then was a full-time Ph.D. student at Bradford.  Whilst I did that, I did three years with SSRC support, and then, of course, in those day
s, you were under no pressure to finish it immediately.  I finished it part-time.  I think, at the time I thought it was taking me far too long, but I think it did only take about four and a half years in the end. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And that was on \'85 ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That was on \'93Wives of the Clergy\'94, that\rquote s right, yes.  Yes.  I mean, \'85
 I had to dream up a topic of some sort, and I can\rquote t really remember how I arrived at that, except that \'85 I\rquote m sure that Esther Goody had some influence on it, because she and I talked a lot ab
out what I might do if I did a Ph.D., and I think I tossed around a number of different ideas.  But, obviously, because of the particular situation that I was in, moving into, she was rather fascinated by it, and I became rather fascinated by it, and it l
inked into my past interest in the sociology of marriage, and also into my growing awareness of second-wave Feminism.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Mmm.  Mmm.  I\rquote m thinking that, I know you don\rquote 
t want to talk much about the marriage side, but, in fact, from what you\rquote re saying, it sounds as if you weren\rquote t really a clergyman\rquote s wife, in the normal sense!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  Well, yeah, I mean \'85 it depends \'85
 The normal sense, perhaps, is not quite as normal as, you know, you might think, or even as I thought then.  But I, certainly, was quite different from most of the people I was interviewing, that\rquote s perfectly true.  And, I mean, I wasn\rquote 
t uninvolved, I was quite involved in \'85 running Youth Groups and that sort of thing, and I certainly attended church and everything.  I mean, I was a practising Christian, in a way, at that stage. \'85 But I never - I knew, for sure, that I didn
\rquote t want to make being married a career, if you see what I mean.  I was absolutely certain of that.  And so getting a Ph.D. was one way of not doing that! I didn\rquote 
t, at that stage, necessarily think I was going into an academic career. Actually, it wasn\rquote t really part of a well-planned move, \'85
 but certainly I knew that getting a Ph.D. would keep me occupied full-time, during that period, and would stand me in good stead in the future, whatever I did decide to do. \'85
 I had - there was a period of three months between leaving Cambridge and starting my Ph.D., and that\rquote s the only time in my life that I hadn\rquote t had my own income, and I really hated it.  I really felt dimini
shed by it.  And so I knew that, you know, I was never going to do that again, basically!  (LAUGHS)  Even though everything else was very \'85 you know, fine, I really didn\rquote t like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Can you speak a little bit more about the idea of studying w
hat you were doing yourself?  That wasn\rquote t very common.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, it wasn\rquote t.  No, not at all.  I don\rquote t think \'85 In fact, I\rquote 
m sure that I wasn\rquote t doing it as an autobiographical exercise, even a kind of pre-autobiography, as a sort of \'85 research methodology.
  I was very clear that the reason why I was doing it was because I thought that there were interesting intellectual questions about the position of somebody who was, as I subsequently came to describe it, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Married to the Job}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 .  And interesting intellectual 
questions, from a sociological perspective, and from a Feminist perspective.  And when I started it, \'85
 what I expected to find, and I suppose my research questions, at the beginning, were all geared to this, what I expected to find was that there would be 
quite clear tensions showing between a conventional expectation that clergy wives were part of the package that went along with the clergyman, and the desire of those same women to lead independent lives.  We\rquote 
re talking, here, about the early seventies, when \'85
 that was the expectation.  So I expected to be doing a piece of work which was exposing those tensions, and which, perhaps, demonstrated the dissatisfaction of women with that situation.  In fact, a year or so into the research, when I\rquote 
d got quite a lot of data already collected, I think \'85 there was quite a sort of turning point when I realised that this was not what I was finding, and that I \'85
 I had to understand what I was seeing, in a much more sociologically sophisticated way.  And that took me quite a long time to work through, because there weren\rquote 
t really very many anchor points in sociology, at that time, that could help me.  And it was the experience of being in the Sociology Department at Bradford that made me realise that \'85 well, I basically h
ad to re-learn sociology at that stage, because it certainly was completely different.  I didn\rquote t recognise anything when I went into the Sociology Department at Bradford in 1970.  I recognised practically nothing from my undergraduate education.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 How was it different, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Well, it was, it was almost entirely theoretical, as far as I could see, and it was all about theory, and it was all about competing theories.  So the competing theories were kind of Althusserian/Marxism, I suppose \'85 Marxis
m, anyway.  In fact, different versions of Marxism.  The \'85 what did they call it?  The Deviancy Symposium? The National Deviancy Symposium.  That\rquote s all that stuff about deviancy that, which \'85
 I now realise, drew on quite a lot of American theoretical literature that I wasn\rquote 
t familiar with either.  There was that.  I then remember that we were hit with ethnomethodology at one point, which was a complete mystery to me!  I had had to read Marx, Weber, and Durkheim, as an undergraduate student, but it was a cho
re to pass that paper.  I didn\rquote 
t really ever think of it as really being about the sort of sociology that I was interested in.  And in that environment, I remember John Eldridge, who did kindly supervise me, saying to me, very gently, at one point, \'93Yes, I
 think we do need to get you some basic sociology\'94  (LAUGHS)  \'93I don\rquote t think you\rquote ve got this quite fixed\'94
, you know.  And so I had to put myself through a new sociology degree, basically, and, of course, I did pick and choose somewhat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what about the Feminism, was that through the Department? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  There was \'85
 Sheila Allen was in the Department at Bradford, at that stage.  Well, she stayed there, in fact, till she retired.  And she was a very very positive influence \'85 There was a group of
 women Ph.Ds., because they had a lot of Ph.D. students then.  There was a group of women, a small group of women Ph.D. students, who she was very supportive of, on a personal basis, and she was very much an influence on thinking through Feminist ideas th
en, in the Department.  I mean, that was, that was a very important strand to me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yes.  I was wondering whether there were any particular people in that group that were important?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 The person who I worked most closely with on, and shared a 
room with, on Feminist issues, was Verity Kahn, who, I don\rquote t know if she\rquote s still in academic life, actually, but at that stage, she was \'85
 she was an anthropologist by background, and she was doing a very innovative study on Muslim families in Bradford and 
Pakistan.  It was a transnational study, what we would now call a transnational study, actually.  And that was good, because that introduced me to a new range of issues.  And she was very supportive of that. \'85
 Well, the other research students that I can recall, were people who were a negative influence on me.  I mean, there was one person, whose name I probably shouldn\rquote 
t mention, because he is still in academic life, who came a year later than me, so I had already completed one year, and I was slogging away, driving all over West Yorkshire, interviewing clergy wives, and he \'85
 was doing something entirely theoretical, and he was very super confident. And I remember, in one of our research student seminars, after he\rquote d been there, I think, less than six months, he announced that he thought he\rquote 
d probably completed about the first one-third of his thesis, and he would easily do the rest of it before the three years were up, and so he was looking for other things to do.  And I was so \'85 undermined by the sense that, you know, he really knew 
\'85 he\rquote d cracked it, he knew what it was about, and this was how you should do it, and I was going completely wrong, and I couldn\rquote t do it, and I lost quite a lot of confidence at that point, actually.  It subsequently gave me great
 satisfaction to see that his career hasn\rquote t gone all that well, actually!  Well, I mean, he may think it\rquote s gone well, but \'85 he hasn\rquote t written, let\rquote 
s put it that way!  (LAUGHS)  But that was many years later!  But it did actually undermine my confidence quite significantly at the time!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And the plan of the interviewing, that came from your earlier training?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yes, I think so.  Yes, I think I saw an interview methodology as being the obvious thing to do, partly from the sort of anthropological experience in Cambridge, and partly because it was that kind of study that I\rquote 
d been familiar with in my undergraduate years.  John, of course, I now know, was quite sympathetic to that approach, and encouraged it.  And so I had a very carefully plan
ned, it was a quite well-planned project, actually, carefully thought through selection procedures and that kind of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 For the sample? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1773805\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yeah, how to do the sample, how to \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So how did you do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 How did I do it?  I took 
the Anglican Diocese of Bradford, and interviewed people in four denominations, within the geographical boundaries encompassed by the Anglican Diocese.  And so that was Anglican, Methodist, Baptist, and Congregationalist \'85
Those [first] two, I think, subseq
uently merged, but they were separate at that stage.  And so I defined it by geographical area.  I then got, got the complete list of clergy, and sampled different fractions, according to the size of the churches, so that I ended up with not equal numbers
,
 but numbers which would enable me to make comparisons.  So that meant I sampled proportionately a lot fewer of the Anglicans than I did of the Non-Conformist denominations.  And then I went off and interviewed them wherever they were.  And, I mean, it wa
s far too ambitious.  I would never \'85 Subsequently, when I started supervising research students myself, I was horrified at the scale that I\rquote d been allowed to \'85
 It was something like 150, which I conducted, transcribed them all myself, analysed them.  Probably not terribly, you know, not as thoroughly as one would do now, but \'85 I did everything myself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 This was an open-ended type interview, was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yeah.  Yeah.  I had, I had an interview schedule of sorts, but they were pretty open-ended, and some of them lasted for hours!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what did you do with all that material?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, I\rquote m sorry to say, Paul, that when I left Lancaster, I threw it away.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, that\rquote s very sad.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I\rquote d kept it until 1995.  The only thing that I\rquote ve got le
ft is a copy of the thesis.  I have looked.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1773805 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I was thinking, you\rquote ve mentioned various people, I\rquote d quite like to talk about them a little bit more.  John Eldridge \'85}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1773805   }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 John Eldridge.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  He\rquote s a terrific person.  And I think he\rquote 
s been a great figure in British sociology, actually, because, quietly, in the background, he has kept a very sane and balanced approach to what good sociology is, whilst the waves of fashion have come and gone.  But he\rquote 
s been involved in some really important initiatives, you know, like the Drug and Media Group and so on, was one of the things that he really did.  And so it\rquote s not that he\rquote s been the kind of boring background figure, far from it, but he
\rquote s actually kept that sense of, of a keen intellectual sense, about what counts as good sociology.  And I think he\rquote 
s been a terrific figure, I have to say.  He was in the Bradford Department at that stage, when I went, and recruited me, as my supervisor.  But I\rquote d only been there for 18 months when he went to Gl
asgow.  And at that stage, and these were the days when people didn\rquote t think about supervision quite in the way we do now, at that stage, he said, \'93Well, you\rquote 
re quite well on with your interviews now.  I can continue to supervise you, if you need it\'94, kind 
of thing.  Nominally, somebody else has to do it, so, nominally, Sheila Allen became my supervisor, but it was entirely agreed between everybody that she wouldn\rquote t do anything, and she didn\rquote 
t. She had a group of women Ph.D. students, and we met regularly and so on, but she didn\rquote 
t do anything, specifically, in relation to my supervision, and nobody ever intended that it should be so.  And there was John in Glasgow.  So I, basically, didn\rquote t have a supervisor for the rest of the time.  John was wonderful.  When
ever I sent him something to read, he wrote back good comments on it, but I thought \'85 I couldn\rquote t bother him too much, you know, so I didn\rquote 
t do that very often.  And I went up to Glasgow once, I think, for about three days, when I was at quite an advanced s
tage.  I probably had quite a lot of the thesis in first draft form, at that stage, and I went up and we worked together, over the three days, quite a lot.  So I felt that when, when he engaged with my supervision, he gave me a very good deal, but it real
ly wasn\rquote t very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what sort of a personality was he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
John?  Very easy person to get on with.  Quite laid-back.  A mixture of being laid-back and intellectually sharp.  Always supportive.  Never felt that he had any difficulty in dealin
g with women.  Very good at that.  Very good at dealing with you, you know, just as he would have done with male Ph.D. students, I think.  Altogether somebody I very much admire.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And Sheila Allen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Sheila?  I love her dearly!  I was asked to 
give the speech about Sheila at her Retirement Party in Bradford, which I was very pleased to be able to do.  And I understand that, subsequently, because I was sent an SOS, that the person who had to do the oration when Bradford subsequently gave her an 
Honorary Degree, recycled my speech!  I think \'85I have the official version of Sheila Allen!  Sheila was an influence which was \'85
 was less intellectually academic, and more about what women can do, in the profession of sociology, and the role of women in the profession of sociology.  I kept in touch with her, long after I left Bradford, through the various women\rquote 
s networks that were set up through the BSA, you know, they took different forms at different times.  But she was wonderful.  She and Margaret Stacey
 were the main, the established women professors, who were the mainstays in the seventies and early eighties, who encouraged other women to get on and do things, and not to be \'85 And they went off, if necessary, and told the men that they\rquote 
d got to let these young women do whatever and so on.  They were terrific, both of them, in quite different ways.  And so, Sheila was that kind of influence on me. She was always \'85 I\rquote ve told these stories about her in her presence, so there
\rquote s no embarrassment about telling 
them here.  She was always somebody who wanted to stay up late, talking, at conferences, and she always outlasted the younger women, you know!  And that sort of thing.  But she was very, I mean, very much respected the long experience that she\rquote 
d had in higher education.  For example, I remember her telling me, and I said this in my retirement speech, and she said she couldn\rquote 
t remember it, but I remember it very vividly, I remember her telling me once how awful it was to be a woman university lecturer in the
 sixties, before the abortion legislation changed, because you were the person who every female student who got themselves pregnant, came to for advice, and you never knew what to do.  You know, do you tell them, \'93Well, this is how you get an abortion
\'94, knowing that it\rquote 
s illegal, or what?  And it was a terrible position to be in.  But she would be the sort of person who would have, characteristically, spent her time with those students, you know.  That was really what being in academic life was for her \endash  su
pporting students, supporting younger staff, and that kind of thing.
\par 
