\'85 Well, anyway, so he moved on to a sort of kind of more independent Parish exist
ence, after three years, which was the norm.  And that was in Hull.  So I moved with him to Hull.  I remained registered at Bradford on a part-time basis, so I was continuing to work on the Ph.D.  And, in fact, I think I still was doing some interviews af
ter we\rquote 
d moved to Hull.  But we were living in Hull, and I needed to find something to earn money, so I went back to school teaching, part-time school teaching, so that I had time to finish the Ph.D..  I knew that if I tried to get a full-time job, it would
 be quite difficult.  So I worked, part-time, as a school teacher, in a comprehensive in East Hull, which was a really rough comprehensive.  That was quite challenging, and I think, although I did okay, and at the point when I left, they very much wanted 
me to stay, I think it finally taught me that school teaching was not the career for me, because up till that point, I didn\rquote t know \'85 I wasn\rquote t sure that academia was, and certainly some of these experiences that I\rquote 
d had with Bradford, with terribly confident young men who were heading for careers, and me, who, you know, thought that I probably wasn\rquote t good enough, I don\rquote 
t think I had the confidence to think that I would get a permanent post in the University.  So I didn\rquote t really, wasn\rquote t really planning an academic career.  School teaching, because I\rquote 
d done it before, was the obvious fall back, as it were.  But I think the experience of teaching in a comprehensive there, made me realise that that probably was not what I wanted to do.  It was very demanding.  And
 even though I was doing it only part-time, I sort of enjoyed it, but I didn\rquote 
t really want to continue.  So I then, opportunistically, applied for a full-time teaching post in what was then one of the Colleges of Education in Hull.  So I think I, for the f
irst year or something, that I was in Hull, I was part-time teaching, and then I did two years in, in what was then Endsleigh College, which was a Roman Catholic College, Teacher Training College, actually.  But by that stage, at that stage, in the mid-se
venties, the Teacher Training Colleges were diversifying into other sorts of programmes as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what were you teaching?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I taught sociology.  I taught sociology.  I taught sociology of education to the \'85
 students who were in teacher training, and I taught sociology, \'85 wide range of sociology courses, to students who were doing a Bachelor\rquote s in Sociology, which was validated by Hull University, I think, not the CNNA.  I can\rquote 
t quite remember that, but I think it was Hull University was doing 
the validation.  I remember, I had 21 hours a week teaching, contact hours teaching, and I was teaching sociology of all sorts, you know, all sorts of sociology courses.  I remember I did Sociology of Work and Industry, which I\rquote 
d never done anything on before, preparing that and so on, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
 I finished my Ph.D. at the same time.  You know, it seems absolutely impossible now, but anyway, I did.  And I did two years there. At that stage, my husband was due for another move, because that was how it worked in the Church of England \endash 
 three years, three years, and then a longer period.  And we decided that he would follow me next time, and if I was able to get \'85 He was, he was very instrumental in persuading me that having, by that stage, got a Ph.D., and got some t
eaching experience, it was not unreasonable to think that I might get a job in a university.  I mean, I still didn\rquote t really have quite that confidence myself.  And he said, \'93Go on, apply\'94.  And I said, \'93Oh, all right, I\rquote 
ll have a go.  And I\rquote ll have a go at the next two or three things that come up, that I can vaguely apply for, if they\rquote re in places where we think we might like to move to\'94
.  And the first one that came up was a post in Lancaster, where I applied for, and got.  And he then \'85 did whatever you do in the Church of England, to organise these things, and moved to a Parish in Preston.
