\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So you get to Lancaster then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Yes.  Where I stayed for 19 years!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, I need to focus on the different stages, I think.  So, I mean, why don\rquote 
t you talk about the first part, when you\rquote re basically teaching there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, I\rquote m not sure that \'85
 Had I thought through what kind of university post I wanted to apply for, I might not have appl
ied for the one that I did apply for.  It really was the first one that I could reasonably apply for, you know, just to see whether I could get it, and I did.  And at the interview, I more or less decided that I was going to refuse it, if I got it.  I rea
lly didn\rquote t like what I saw.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 What didn\rquote t you like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 There were two things that I didn\rquote t like.  One was \'85
 well, it was a new Department, the Department of Social Administration, as it then was called.  They had advertised for a sociologist.  It was very much on the LSE model.  I\rquote 
ll come back to that in a minute, the Social Administration Department at the LSE, where you have something from all the basic disciplines, social science disciplines, sort of bearing upon policy issues.  And so they were
 trying to recruit a psychologist, a sociologist, and an economist, and so on, and so that I was recruited as a sociologist.  Thus far, so good.  But I didn\rquote 
t really have much feel for what a Department of Social Administration might really be like.  And w
hen I was recruited, they were trying to appoint six staff, all at once, and they held the interviews all together, over a period of three or four days, or something like that.  And so I was in, I think they interviewed 30 people, or something like that, 
over three or four days.  And so the first exposure to it was an enormous kind of reception, in which quite a lot of other people knew each other, because they\rquote d been in the social administration type circles, which I hadn\rquote 
t, and I found it altogether very alienating.  And so that was one reason why I didn\rquote 
t like it.  And the second reason, very specifically, the then Vice-Chancellor, Charles Carter, chaired the Appointing Committee, and his first question to me was, \'93If you move here, what will your husband do?\'94  And I\rquote 
d put nothing on my application form to indicate that I was married, or anything like that.  One of my referees, presumably, must have said something.  And I was completely thrown by that.  It was an outrageous question.  It was 1976, after th
e Sex Discrimination Act came into force, so it was actually unlawful, and I just thought, \'93I don\rquote t want to be in a place like this\'94.  But because the \'85 process was so protracted, they didn\rquote 
t complete it, and it was several days later when I got a phone call saying, \'93Will you take the job?  We really want you\'94.  And I said, \'93No, I really \'85 I don\rquote t think \'85 I don\rquote t want to\'94
.  And Roger Hadleigh, who was Head of the Department, and who was setting it up, said, \'93Oh, come on, think about it.  We really would like you\'94. And, you know, he \'85 he was a lovely man.  He\rquote s died recently.  And I said, \'93
Okay.  Give me a few days.  I will think about it\'94.  And eventually, I decided to take it.  I liked him, he did talk me into it, up to a point.  My then husband quite liked the idea of moving to Lancashire, and \'85
 so I decided to, in the end.  So thus I ended up in, as a sociologist in a Social Administration Department.  And it was a Department which was very new, so that the year that I was appointed was the first year that
 any students came to study Social Administration in Lancaster.  Roger Hadleigh had been recruited from the LSE, to establish the Department.  He had worked very closely with Titmuss, it was a very Titmuss-oriented Department.  He, himself \'85
 I was going to say, wasn\rquote t really a researcher.  That\rquote 
s probably terribly unfair to him, because he was very influential on quite a lot of research.  But he was, basically, an activist.  And the things that he was interested in were the voluntary sector, co-operatives.  He\rquote 
d done an early study of workers\rquote  co-operatives, and he was interested about how you translate that into a social welfare kind of environment.  Those sorts of things.  He was, \'85
 from the point at which I went to Lancaster, very much involved in what was, I think, the Wolfenden Commission on the Role of the Voluntary Sector, and he was away a lot doing that.  He was that, that kind of thing, rather than, \'93Now, you\rquote 
ve just got your Ph.D..  What\rquote s the next thing you should be doing?\'94 you know.  And so I, there was no \'85
 first of all, there was no mentoring of any sort, in the research sense.  Secondly, the group of people that he had put together was a real mixture, because the Department had Social Work as well, so some people were recruited from being Prob
ation Officers and that sort of thing, with no research background, or very little.  And thirdly, the ethos of universities, at that time, was really quite teaching-oriented, and particularly that generation of universities.  At Lancaster the emphasis was
 very much on being innovative, and doing a very good job in teaching students.  And all of these conspired to make it an environment in which research was not really expected, actually.  And I remember, from the very beginning, feeling, \'93This isn
\rquote t right.  I know I\rquote ve got to go on and do research, and anyway, I want to\'94, and because I was involved in the BSA, I had some sort of other reference points, nationally, I knew that I wanted to \'85
 But it really was several years before I got into my stride with research.  And I, I started by trying to work out what I could publish from my thesis.  And the first thing I ever published was, in fact, an article in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid14692840 Sociological Review}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , from my thesis, which I was quite pleased with, because I knew that getting something 
into a peer reviewed journal was a good idea.  I then had an unsuccessful attempt to develop book proposals based just on the thesis.  And a person who was very helpful to me, at that time, was John Wakeford, who was in the Sociology Department at Lancast
er, and he \'85 I think he must have had a book series that he was editing for one of the big publishers, or something like that, so I talked to him about it, and he had a go at helping me to approach a couple of publishers, where it didn\rquote 
t work.  And in the end, it was he who said, \'93Look here, I think that something like this is not broad enough to have the kind of appeal as an academic work\'94.  I knew that I could probably write something popular, but I didn\rquote 
t want to do that.  \'93It doesn\rquote t really have a broad enough \'85\'94  \'93So how could you broaden it?\'94 \'93Could you think about making comparisons between what you\rquote ve done, and what other people have done?\'94
 and so on. It was out of that discussion that the idea of doing what turned out to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Married to the Job}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  was bor
n.  I got quite excited by the thought of comparison.  And then I began to think, something that has actually, I think, been characteristic of all my subsequent work, which is that the sort of comparisons between X, Y and Z, never should be just comparati
ve between X, Y and Z, because \'93Gosh, isn\rquote t that interesting to compare X with Y and with Z\'94
, but because there is some underlying strand that links them, there is a research question there which links them, and of which each of them is an example.  And you find out about the underlying issue by making these comparisons, but they\rquote 
re not comparisons for their own sake.  And so, you know, the underlying research questions in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Married to the Job}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  are about whether there is something about the nature of marriage t
hat takes particular forms in marriages where a man has a certain kind of occupation, and an occupation in which there is some kind of imperative, whether it be born of external expectations, or something inherent in the logic of the job, like, you know, 
a house goes with the job, or something like that, which draws women in, but that it\rquote s not necessarily that there\rquote s this category of jobs that women get involved in, and then the rest of the jobs that they don\rquote t.  That there\rquote 
s something inherent in the nature of marriage that has this particular manifestation with those sort of jobs.  I\rquote m saying all of this, I haven\rquote t read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Married to the Job}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  for years, actually!  (LAUGHS)  I\rquote m not sure that that comes through, but my retrospective account of what I was doing there, was that.  And that
\rquote s the sort of approach that I\rquote d think underlines, underlies a lot of the subsequent work that I\rquote ve done, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, can you say a bit more about how you did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
