\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And they\rquote re with both the man and the woman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I don\rquote t remember that, actually.  I don\rquote t remember whether they \'85
 whether there were separate interviews with the women or not, or whether it all came from the men\rquote s interviews, \'85 I can\rquote t recall that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 It\rquote s an interesting instance of a re-study, isn\rquote t it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Yes.  Well, not a re
-study, a re-use of the data, which is what your Data Archive is all about, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Did you think about it, at the time, in that way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, I didn\rquote t think \'85 Well, no, I was aware that \'85
 well, because she and I were interested in methodology, we talked about the methodological issues of it, and I think I was aware, at that time, that \'85 I could never go back into her data and expect to come out with the same book that she\rquote 
d written, if you like.  You always bring your own interpretation to it.  And that was very obvious, because in this particular instance, I was looking for something completely different from what she\rquote 
d been looking for.  So the data that I was using was \'85not quite, but almost incidental to the project that she\rquote d been pursuing.
  So I was conscious that it was a process in which I was doing something different with the same set of data, from the person who\rquote d originally collected it.  So, from that point of view, I sort of thought about the methodological issues, but I don
\rquote t think I thought of it as a re-study or anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes, as you say, re-analysis.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Re-analysis, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 But there is a lot of inhibition really, isn\rquote 
t it, when using qualitative methods, in looking at somebody else\rquote s data.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes. 
 Yes.  Well, it was quite interesting, because I was entirely clear that Maureen wouldn\rquote t have let me anywhere near it, unless I got to know her fairly well \'85
 Not only personally, perhaps, more importantly, intellectually, so that she, I think, had confidence in what I would do with it, that what I would do with it would not compromise what she thought should be done with it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 What sort of a person is she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Maureen?  Oh, I mean, with a completely different background to me.  Very much more straightforward sociologist.  Knowledge of all sorts of things that I didn\rquote 
t know much about.  Much more theoretical.  She introduced me to some quite heavy theory, actually, which was good for me, because I hadn\rquote t properly engaged with it when I was an underg
raduate student, partly because there was so much of it, it was intellectual indigestion almost!  And so, yes, I got into all the Althusserian stuff and understood it a bit more, through her, and some of the other strands of Marxism which were influential
 in sociological theory at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
But, in a way, one of the things that you end with, is the way [in which women internalise their situation]. It\rquote s almost like false consciousness, isn\rquote t it, really, and I wonder how you got on to that? Was that in your thesis as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yes, it was.  It was, actually.  Perhaps not quite so prominently, and not so sociologically worked through as in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Married to the Job}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , but \'85 but it was, yes, it was there.
  I mean, it was a product of this kind of switch that I had some part way through doing the Ph.D., where I thought I was going to find one thing, and actually, I was finding something completely different, and had to start from scratch, looking for socio
logical tools which could help me to understand the empirical situation that I was observing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
One of the things that strikes me about it is that [you were writing this complex interpretation] in the early seventies, during the first stage of the seco
nd wave Feminism, and you were involved in that.  How did that fit with the rather simpler views that a lot of people had?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yeah.  I think it made me \'85
 it made me certain that I wanted to understand the empirical situations I was studying, namely the role of clergymen\rquote s wives, with perspectives that had gender very much at their heart, that you couldn\rquote 
t understand that.  Because, essentially, what I was looking at was the dynamics of marriage.  I couldn\rquote t conceive of producing an analysis of that which wasn\rquote 
t strongly influenced by a sociological understanding of gender which, at that stage, was very much sort of almost lifted from Feminism.  I think we became much more sophisticated later on.  But this was not, \'85 this didn\rquote 
t feel totally new, because
 going back to, you know, the way McGregor taught me about marriage, there was a very strong gender component in that.  So it came fairly naturally, actually.  Now, I may have used it, I probably did use it in a rather unsophisticated way, perhaps particu
larly in the thesis, but I think that was the influence of Feminism.  [But] it wasn\rquote t that - I don\rquote t think, in fact I couldn\rquote t have - imposed Feminist explanations straightforwardly on what I was seeing, because \'85
such as they were, they weren\rquote t terribly relevant to the situation that I was looking at.  So it had to be a more creative process than that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
And two of the circles you mentioned as being influential, in the book, one is a group at Lancaster, the Women\rquote s Research Group.  Is it worth saying something about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yeah.  Yeah, I\rquote 
m quite proud of having been in at the early stages of that, because Lancaster has developed some very good research on gender subsequently.  Yes, \'85 from probably about 1978 onwards, somewhere thereabouts, there w
ere enough women in different Departments in Lancaster, to initially get together, just very informally, to meet, to talk, we just gave papers about our own research, read books and commented on them, had reading evenings, that sort of thing \'85
 very active little group, from about 1978 onwards.  Subsequently that group spawned teaching programmes in Women\rquote s Studies, and got much bigger.  But the small Group, now, I probably can\rquote 
t remember everybody who was in it.  But Sylvia Walby who came to the Sociology D
epartment in 1978, from Essex, having been supervised by Mary McIntosh, and who was very much into Feminist theory, and Penny Summerfield, who is one of my closest friends still, who is a historian of the Second World War \'85
 you probably know Penny, do you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
[She] came in 1978 as well.  The three of us probably were the people who, maybe because we were in secure positions, were the core of it.  Oh, Alison Easton in the English Department, as well, was very much involved at the early stage
s, and still is.  And those of us who were in secure positions probably were the most important ones.  We then had a number of other people who were, you know, some research students doing Feminist work, research staff on short-term contracts, and that ki
nd of thing, but we were probably the most important ones.  And that was, that, along with the BSA, which we\rquote ll talk about, was very much my intellectual home, at that stage, not the Department that I was working in, with one exception, which I
\rquote ll come back to.  But, but that, really, those people were \'85
 I mean, we were very different people, with very different substantive intellectual interests, but very much all of us seeing the kind of Feminist theory, and, for my part, its influence on sociology, as the
 intellectual leading edge, and what we wanted to be able to pursue.  So it was very much a mixture of the intellectual and the personal.  And we began with research, not with teaching.  The teaching programmes came a bit later.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Were there any particular ideas that came out from that Group?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I don\rquote 
t think I could pinpoint anything that came out from the Group, but I think the \'85 all the people who I\rquote ve mentioned as the core of the group, have had very successful academic careers subsequently.  
And I think that the influence we had on each other, has probably been quite important.  The only person in the Department of Social Administration, who was involved in any way, and she was a bit more marginal, I think, probably, was Dulcie Groves, with w
h
om I did publish a number of things subsequently.  And that, that was another strand of what was going on then.  Because I was in a policy oriented Department, I naturally did become involved in a number of research issues, or become involved in issues wh
i
ch then turned into a research interest, which were about social policy.  And Dulcie Groves and I started working, probably around 1980, on something which was quite separate from these other things that I was doing, except that Feminism was a link, which
 was about community care, the government\rquote 
s community care policies at that time.  It was very Departmentally specific, actually.  Roger Hadleigh, because of his interest in the voluntary sector, and non-State sorts of provision, was quite in the vanguard o
f the then movement to focus on informal care, as opposed to formal, State provided care, as a much more acceptable method of providing support for \'85 well, any category of people who can\rquote 
t look after themselves, but particularly we were all interested in o
lder people.  And he was very much involved politically, personally, academically, in all of that.  And it was totally non-gendered.  And it used to drive Dulcie and me up the wall, because he\rquote 
d come in and talk, you know, at great length, and with enormous enthusiasm, because he was a man of very great enthusiasm, about all this.  And we would say, \'93Well, haven\rquote t you noticed that it\rquote s women who do it all?\'94 you know!  \'93
No, no, no, that\rquote s just incidental\'94, etc. \'85 Subsequently, he actually became very sensitive to gender in his work.  But at that stage, he wasn\rquote 
t.  And we actually got so annoyed with this, that we decided we were going to write something.  And we were going to write a critique of his work, and others who were working in this mould \'85 promoting 
the idea of informal care.  And we did it, and we were pretty thorough about it.  We actually wrote it as a conference paper for the Social Policy Association Conference.  I think it was called Social Administration Association in those days.  For their A
nnual Conference.  But, I mean, we put an enormous amount of work into it.  And we gave it at this Conference, and it was greeted with great acclaim.  And it was subsequently published in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Journal of Social Policy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , and it became one of the intellectual a
nchor points for a lot of other work that then developed on gender and caring.  And we, ourselves, then went on to edit a book, which was very influential, and to do more work for journal articles, to make contact with people in other countries, particula
r
ly in Scandinavia, who were beginning to work on similar topics.  And all of that has led me to a lot of other things that have been very intellectually stimulating in my academic life.  But that strand came from a completely different strand to the socio
logical me, if you like \'85 around the same time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes. But it is related to the other strands.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Since you specially mentioned Penny Summerfield and Sylvia Walby, would it be worth saying a word about each of them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Sylvi
a is a great theoretician, and wanted to make her mark as such, and did so.  And as such, I think, is quite a long way away from the sort of sociologist that I am.  We\rquote re probably, really, at quite opposite ends of the spectrum.  So that I don
\rquote t know what she got out of me.  I suspect that the sort of work that I did was not \'85
 really the sort of sociology that she was terribly interested in, for understandable reasons.  I got a lot out of her, particularly in the early stages, when she knew an awful lot mor
e than I did about Feminist theory, and different forms of Feminist theory.  So I learned a great deal from her, intellectually.  We were never particularly close on a personal basis, but she was an important influence on my ability to engage with Feminis
t theory, which \'85 I\rquote m rather out of date on now, I have to say, but at that stage, I would think pretty much on top of.  \tab Penny Summerfield and I were close personal friends from an early stage, and have continued to be so.  We\rquote 
ve never actually \'85 we\rquote ve only ever done one piece of academic work together, which was one article that we wrote on \'93Marriage in the post-War Period\'94
, in the immediate post-War period, between 1945 and 1960, for a book in which there were other articles on subsequently.  So sort of m
arriage and social reconstruction, if you like, which we both thoroughly enjoyed, actually.  And I can imagine working with Penny in the future, though the opportunity has never arisen.  I mean, she is a very, to my mind, a very sociologically oriented hi
storian, whose \'85
 approach to doing academic work and substantive interests, very much coincide with mine.  So we both, though she does historical work and I do contemporary work, we both do, I think, the same sort of work, namely work which is normally \'85 ha
s empirical data in it, of various sorts, but which is pretty theoretically informed.  So this is quite theoretically driven, but can\rquote t survive without data kind of work, that we both do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about the BSA Sexual Divisions Study Group?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 The BSA Sexual Divisions Study Group, BSA Women\rquote 
s Caucus, BSA Family Study Group, to some extent, but a slightly less extent, [are] all enormously important intellectual anchor points for me.  These were the places at which I met, on a regular basis, peopl
e from round the country who were in a similar position to me, with similar interests to me.  And, you know, we did meet much more regularly than, I think, the equivalents meet now \'85
 entirely at our own expense, and very cheaply. We would meet, for example
, in Bradford, because Sheila was often involved in this. We would just meet entirely at our own expense, for a Saturday afternoon, and go off for a curry, and it was great!  And the mixture, often a mixture, well, particularly the Sexual Divisions and th
e Women\rquote s Caucus, usually were only women attending, well, always only women attending Women\rquote s Caucus.  And, you know, so it was often a mixture of intellectual work and plotting women\rquote 
s careers, and how to take over the BSA, and things like that!  Well, not how to take \'85 I don\rquote t think we ever wanted to take it over, but how to become more influential in the BSA, and that kind of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Maybe figure out how to deal with these men you were referring to, who couldn
\rquote t deal with women!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well,
 yes!  Possibly, yes!  (LAUGHS)  I think we were very concerned about patronage, at that stage, and saw our male counterparts, apparently getting permanent academic posts, having done much less than women did when they got them, and that kind of thing, an
d saw structures of patronage as being responsible for that. Which is probably true, but only maybe in part \'85
 And wanting to get organised to try and get women into situations where they became more prominent and so on.  I mean, it was probably through that kind of route that I ended up chairing the BSA Executive at a very early stage in my career.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what year was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, \lquote 83-\rquote 84.  \lquote 83-\rquote 
84.  I was on the Executive from 1980.  It was Margaret Stacey that did that.  She persuaded me to stand for the Executive.  And I remember, almost can remember the words, actually!  I remember her saying \'85
 well, it was all part of the sort of general understanding that we\rquote ve got to get women into these positions, in order to get women into positions of influ
ence, where they could help other women, and that kind of thing.  And, of course, I did have a secure academic position at that point.  And she said, she was on some sort of Research Committee for Executive Members, and she said, \'93They\rquote 
re all coming at me, these male names.  And I\rquote m not having it.  I\rquote ve told them we\rquote ve got to have a better mix.  And we\rquote ve got to look for people who can do the job.  And you can do it, Janet, so you\rquote ve got to do it\'94
.  And I said, \'93I\rquote m not ready\'94.  \'93Yes, come on, I\rquote m telling you you\rquote ve got to do it.  By the way, you\rquote ve also got to write the bloody books as well!\'94  (LAUGHS)  I remember her saying that!  You know, it\rquote 
s a very good piece of advice, actually, because I have seen other people, women and men, but probably more women 
than men, do this sort of thing at an early stage in their career, and get distracted into, you know, having to run a professional Association or something like that, and not actually doing the things that really do matter, in terms of promotion.  So, so 
it was Meg that did that. Then once on the Executive, I don\rquote t rightly remember how I got to it, but I ended up as Vice-Chair to Robert Moore, fairly quickly, and Bob Burgess became Hon. Gen. Sec. around the same time.  Bob\rquote 
s career and mine, from that point on, paralleled each other to a remarkable extent, actually.  And he\rquote 
s a close friend too.  And he and I were both quite junior then, and we worked together.  I was Vice-Chair, he was Hon.Gen. Sec., to sort out a few things and so on.  And I just, I don\rquote t 
remember precisely how I ended up as Chair, but I did, for one year, anyway, which was good fun, though a bit scary!  And, of course, it was, it was at the period when sociology was really under attack.  So I was very much at the heart of that, of trying 
to cope with that.
