\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So, this is our second session, on the 8}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , and we\rquote re going to talk, first of all, about your subsequent research.  And I think that the first one we haven\rquote t talked about is the project, \'93Working-class Women and Pre-School Play Groups\'94.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  That was the first project that I had a secured research grant for, and I \'85
  I realised enough about how you construct a career to \'85 to know that I needed to get a research, I needed to start getting research grants.  And I did something, instinctively, which I\rquote 
ve subsequently encouraged other people to do early in their careers, which was to start with a relatively modest project, which would \'85
 in a sense, get a track record of getting grants, doing it, delivering, and so on.  I mean, I think it was less than \'a32,000, which seemed, to me, a huge amount of money then, well, that wo
uld be more than it is now.  But it was quite small.  It was the first grant application I\rquote 
d ever put in.  I put it in to the SSRC and I got it.  So, I was quite pleased with that.  But it was to support, basically, the incidental costs of doing all the work myself.  The topic, \'93Working-class Women and Pre-School Play Groups\'94
, really came out of \'85 a personal interest. But one which I \'85 I was almost thinking up a topic to get a research grant on, to get the experience of applying and doing a piece of research, which was not anything to do with what I\rquote 
d done for my Ph.D..  It was still, obviously quite a lot of it was about family issues, marriage to an extent, and so on.  But I actually got interested in pre-school play groups whilst I was in Hull, in the per
iod, the first year that I was in Hull, when I was doing some part-time teaching.  I think I must have forgotten to mention, yesterday, because I had forgotten this, that I did \'85
 I did a bit of part-time lecturing in FE as well.  And in the FE College in Hull, they asked me to do a bit of extra work, which was a tailored programme for the Pre-Schools Play Groups Association, training for staff \'85
 for volunteers, who were working with Play Groups, I think.  So, anyway, I did that, and therefore I got to know about the Pre-School Play Group Movement, which I hadn\rquote 
t known much about before, and got quite interested in it from, I suppose, a community development angle, and what role it had within all that. That, somehow, got put together in my head with the inter
est that I was developing in Feminism and gender.  And it, it emerged as a set of questions about the role, about the situations in which women were being used as volunteers, to run what was, essentially, might otherwise have been publicly funded services
.  So it had a \'85
 it had a social policy angle, which, at that stage, because I was working in the Department of Social Administration, I felt somewhat obliged to try and develop a research interest with a social policy angle.  So it had a social policy angl
e, which was quite up-to-date, in that it was a volunteering, voluntary organisation, voluntary sector, running services which might otherwise be State services.  But I got interested particularly in the social class angle, because \'85
 my experience of teaching people who were volunteers, on the programmes in Hull, had made me acutely conscious of the fact that \'85 it was the kind of thing that middle-class women did \endash 
 volunteer to run Play Groups.  And, indeed, part of what we would now call \'93social capital\'94 a
ctually, the reproduction of social capital, in making sure that their children had other children of the same sort to play with, at an early age, and would then go on to meet the right sort of children at primary school, and so on.  And I could see that 
a
ll that was what normally happened in the Pre-School Play Groups, and the Organisation nationally, seemed to me, to very much reflect that kind of tone, if you like.  But I knew that they were trying to expand, and, indeed, I think, probably were able to 
g
et some funding from government to expand into the very deprived areas.  But they were trying to expand in such a way that actually maintained this principle, that it was mothers who run the Play Group for their own children, if you like.  And it seemed t
o
 me that there were some interesting intellectual questions there, about the way in which gender and social class map on to each other, in the context of something which had the kind of policy orientation that I wanted to develop.  So it was a very intere
sting small project.  I published about four or five articles from it, I think, which I think all are quite different from each other.  I think, I think it was quite a good piece of work, actually, although it\rquote s not something that I\rquote 
ve followed up very much subsequently. It was based on interviews and observation.  So I selected \'85 I think about six, maybe eight \'85
 no, six Pre-School Play Groups, that I identified on the basis that they had the characteristics that I was looking for, which was, essentially, th
e kind of areas that I was looking for.  I identified them through contacting Local Authorities mainly, because Local Authorities have to register Play Groups.  And I did, I think I did 12 months observation, where I just went along, I went along and watc
hed, and wrote field notes on what I saw.  And at the end of the 12 months, I interviewed all the people running the Groups, and a selection of mothers who used them, who weren\rquote 
t involved in running them.  And, in essence, the sort of complete data set is really only on three of the Groups, because the other three, I think it was, that I started with, were in various stages of collapse by the time I\rquote 
d finished the observational period, which, of course, was very interesting in itself, which demonstrated the 
difficulties of sustaining that kind of voluntary organisation, run by volunteers, in that kind of geographical setting.  But, intellectually, I think probably the most, the most interesting work that I did, based on that, was about social deference, prob
a
bly, and about the way in which working-class women, I suppose, in a sense, have a kind of double negative bit of their identity, and what that does to self-confidence, and what it does to the way in which they relate to other women.  Plus, I think probab
ly the best article I wrote on this, was actually given the title, \'93Dividing the Rough and the Respectable\'94
, and it was the very interesting aspect of the data which, in essence, is the basis of an argument which was very much about the historical dividing line within the working-classes, between \'93rough\'94 and \'93respectable\'94
, and the extent to which, first of all, that is very much about women, and how women \'85 organise their family lives, and how they bring up their children, and how that then mapped on to the 
way in which these organisations conducted their affairs.  And, essentially, what you had was women running them, defining themselves as \'93respectable working-class\'94, running organisations where they were dealing with the children of the \'93
rough working-class\'94.  And you occasionally saw people moving between these two boundaries.  But that distinction was most definitely alive and well in some of the more deprived parts of Lancashire in the early 1980s.  And it\rquote 
s got some interesting historical resonances, I 
think.  So I never did anything more along those lines, but I think it was, it was a successful small project.  It gave me another line of publishing.  And, most important of all, it gave me a track record of success, with ESRC, of a successfully complete
d research grant.
