\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I was thinking, though, one of your articles, which I haven\rquote t read, is called 
\'93The Seat of Self-Help\'94?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh yes, that\rquote s right.  I haven\rquote 
t read that for a long time, either.  Well, that\rquote s certainly from the same study.  That, I
 think, actually, that was also quite a good piece of work, I think, arising from this, which linked that much more into the policy issues, if you like, rather than the sociology issues.  That was really about the extent to which \'85
 the agenda itself helped
, which I think we talked about a little bit yesterday, when I was talking about the work I was doing on community care for older people, in the same period.  All in the same period.  The two, to some extent, came together in a critique of the ideas aroun
d
 the informal care, emphasis on voluntary provision, on self-provision.  Not the voluntary sector, as understood in an earlier era, which is formally constituted Voluntary Organisations, running things as if they might have been the Local Authority runnin
g things, but rather the emphasis on people doing things for themselves, which was true both in elderly care and in this Play Groups arena.  And I think I felt, quite strongly [critical], as a result of the work that I\rquote 
d done on Play Groups, and wrote about in that article, that the \'85 The public rhetoric of this was that it would be better \'85
 that there would be all sorts of gains, both for young children, and for their mothers, if they were put in these circumstances, rather than in a State-funded nursery school.  Whereas, in reality, it\rquote 
s back to the argument about social capital, if you like.  In reality, what children of the middle-classes got, in whatever circumstances they were in, in a self-help Play Group, yes, or in the nursery school, was the reprodu
ction of social and cultural capital.  And if middle-class mothers were running Play Groups for their own children, they were giving them that, whereas if you were asking mothers who, themselves, have got very little social capital, and very little educat
ional background, for example, to run Play Groups for their own children, they are denying their children access to that sort of social and cultural capital.  I didn\rquote t put it like that in the article, but that\rquote 
s how I would explain it now, probably.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Now, I know the research for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
