\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 It\rquote s much broader.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Much broader.  Much broader.  That\rquote s it.  No, it\rquote 
s a much broader book.  It was written in a series which was not a textbook series, but a series more aimed at the student market than I\rquote d written for before.  When I went to Lancaster in \rquote 76, I think I explained, when we were
 talking yesterday, that I was recruited as a sociologist, into a Department which was meant to have one of everything, as it were.  But I was also recruited with a substantive specialism in education, which, I have to say, I didn\rquote 
t really have, and told them that I didn\rquote t have.  But because I\rquote 
d previously been teaching in a Teacher Training institution, it was deemed to be enough.  And they wanted somebody to teach the education strand of a social administration programme, and I think it was actually called \'93Educational Administration\'94
 in the early days.  Not for long!  And so I set about devising an education course, to be taught as part of the Social Administration degree, with very little to go on, actually, because \'85 I don\rquote t think it was taught in many,
 in many Social Administration degrees, in those days.  But it had been taught at the LSE, and Roger was very much, Roger Hadleigh was very much wedded to that model.  And so I taught, for many years, actually, a course on education within the Social Admi
n
istration, subsequently Social Policy degree.  And I suppose I set about devising a course which was utilising my skills as a sociologist, if you like.  So I think it was rather different from courses that were taught elsewhere.  And when I was approached
 by the \'85 it was in a series of Social Policy books, when I was approached by the Series Editor about doing the education book in that series, I was rather keen on the idea, because \'85
 you know, I need my own teaching materials, but I knew that there wasn\rquote t 
a book that treated education as I believed that it should be treated, which was capable of being analysed as part of the Welfare State.  It goes right back to Beveridge, you know.  One of the giants to be slayed was ignorance \'85
 And education, 1944 Educati
on Act was conceived as being one of the key foundations of the Welfare State.  But, in fact, the academic study of education had drifted off into other areas, and being dominated much more by the sociology of education, as understood within sociology.  N
ot very much developed within social administration.  And I felt that there was a real need there to make a statement about how, about how far education was part of the Welfare State initiative.  So that\rquote 
s what the book is.  It maps out that territory, in a variety of different ways, and follows a formula of the series, which is that there are a number of extracts from public policy documents, Royal Commissions, and that sort of thing included.  So it
\rquote s quite an extensive documentary section in the back.  And then the chapters, obviously, draw on those documents as part of the commentary.  And I used concepts like \'93education as social engineering\'94, and \'85
 to get underneath the skin of where it fitted in, and highlighted some things like the role of the Educati
on Welfare Service, for example, which was very much not commented on.  But I conceived of it as something which I wanted to do because I had a teaching interest in that area.  I don\rquote t think that I was ever \'85
well, I think, looking back on it, it is a very serious piece of research, actually, but I never thought of it as being something which was opening up a new area of research for me.  I wrote it, I had a year\rquote 
s sabbatical leave in 1981-2, and at that point in my life, I realised that I\rquote d got to write.  I\rquote d got to really start writing.  At that point I decided that I was in for the long haul with an academic career.  I\rquote 
d made a reasonably good start.
\par 
