\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 \rquote 86.  I must have started working on that \'85 I wasn\rquote 
t working on that at the same time as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Education and Social Policy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , I don\rquote t 
think.  I mean, that\rquote s a different sort of book altogether.  By the time I started working on this, \'85 I was very much interested in methodology, and had adopted broadly qualitative methodology in all the research that I\rquote 
d done to that date, and \'85 was quite
 actively involved, I think, in national discussions about qualitative methods, and the development of qualitative methods at that time, and the arguments about the legitimacy of qualitative methods.  I then was asked by Bob Burgess, who was a Series Edit
or of \'85  I think it was Falmer Press then \'85 He was editing a series of books on qualitative methods, and asked me to do one on education.  I remember that I did hesitate for some time, because I didn\rquote t want, really, to become an educational 
\'85 I was fairly sure that I didn\rquote 
t want to develop my identity as an educational researcher, if you like.  But, but when I thought about it, I thought there was a book that I could do, which would be quite demanding for me, and something fairly different, but which I would
 quite like to do, and so it was, the subtitle was \'93Social and Educational Research\'94
, but all the illustrations were from education, all the substantive illustrations were from education, but the arguments were really about the use of qualitative methods in social policy research.  And I don\rquote 
t really think many other people have taken it much further than that, I have to say.  Social Policy, as a discipline, Social Administration/Social Policy, as a discipline, has always been fairly unsophisticated about m
ethods.  Maybe that would be an unfair comment right now, but \'85 certainly in the eighties, and more recently than that, too, you don\rquote 
t find lots of methodologists in Social Policy.  And I felt that there were two problems that I was aware of, which I wante
d, in a sense, to try and address in that book.  One was in the policy-making arena, the lack of legitimacy of qualitative methods, and the reliance, almost exclusively, on survey type methodology, and demographic analysis, and that kind of thing.  And at
 
the same time, a feeling that there was some legitimacy to the fact that qualitative research was not really regarded in the policy arena because, actually, it was often not very well done.  And so the twin poles of trying to understand what would be the 
g
enuine opportunities for influencing social policy-making decisions, through the use of qualitative research, and at the same time, recognising that in order to do that, you would have to develop an approach to qualitative research and social policy which
 was actually more sophisticated and more rigorous than that, which was then.  So that\rquote s really the book holds those two together, through, through very different means, really.  It\rquote 
s very much a book of two halves.  The first half is largely historical, and it\rquote s about the \'85
 the development of traditions of social policy research in Britain, counterpointing, counterposing the dominant tradition of survey based research, with \'85 a much more submerged, then, more submerged strand, of what you could re-categoris
e as qualitative research, some of which, of course, is the kind of thing which we\rquote ve just been looking at this morning.  But, but you can go back to Mayhew, for example, and trace it through, through the \'85
 inter-War interest in community studies of a certain type, to Mass Observation. I actually did work in the Mass Observation Archive.  That\rquote s the only time I\rquote ve ever done proper historical research.  And since I\rquote 
m not a historian, I wouldn\rquote t even claim that, really!  But I used the Mass Observation Archive to uncover some debates about, about methods, about methods and their relationship to policy.  And that\rquote 
s all in that book.  And so the first half is about the development of different research traditions in social policy research in Britain.  And the second half of it is more addressing \'93in principle\'94
 what could happen, if you like.  And there, all the illustrations come from education.  So evaluating the strengths and weaknesses from a policy perspective of \'85 existing published research, and thinking th
rough the opportunities, drawing very much on the thinking which was being, I think, led by Martin Bulmer at that point in time, about the Enlightenment model of research, the American literature on all of that.  The conclusion is very much about the impo
rtance of qualitative research to social policy, but with an expectation that the influence will be indirect and not direct.  Something which has been \'85 That sort of general conclusion formed very much part of subsequent thinking of where I\rquote 
ve been in social policies.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Were Glaser and Strauss an influence?
