\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s29\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  No, actually \'85 in fact, that one uses the Play Group study.  I\rquote 
d forgotten that.  That actually uses the Play Group study, and my Ph.D. work on clergymen\rquote 
s wives.  Well, you heard me talk about that at the conference that you ran recently.  It was an article which was one of those things, and I have, at many times in my life, ended up doing things because somebody asked me to do it, and I would guess that
\rquote s true of many \'85 particularly for edited collections. It was Helen Roberts who asked me to do this, for the collection that she and Colin Bell were editing, called, I believe it was called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Doing Feminist Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , and it was intended to be a \'85 follow-up to the Bell and Newby collection of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Doing Sociological Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
, which was one of the earliest examples in this country of sort of self-revelatory research that tells what it was really like, kind of thing.  And they were doing this follow-up on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Doing Feminist Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , and Helen had been one of the people, one of the group of women of my age who \'85
 she, actually, was also at Bradford, I think, at the time that I was there, briefly, but around that time the \'85 the BSA Sexual Division Study Group and so on, so I\rquote 
d known Helen for a long time, and sort of was persuaded to do something.  And I remember, I was trying to move house or something, at the time, and had very little time to do it, and I thought, \'93Well, I\rquote ve got to think of something to do\'94
, and did that article, probably at faster speed than most other things that I\rquote ve ever done.  But it turned out to be one of these things that\rquote s got recycled and quoted all over the place, and \'85 I mean, I am, in some ways, s
orry that I wrote it, because I think it\rquote s been, it has been misquoted.  It had been misquoted to \'85 a degree that makes it hardly recognisable to me, though, of course, I suppose the worst examples are in Finals papers and so on!  You know, it
\rquote s one of those things that comes back to haunt you when you\rquote re \'85
 External Examiner somewhere or other, and you find that Finch wrote something that you absolutely disagree with, and never would have dreamed of writing!  But I think, I think it was quite important, in 
some ways, to my thinking about methodology, in that it was engaging with the debates about the ethics, the ethics of research, if you like, and particularly the ethics of the relationship between the researcher and research subject, which did influence t
he way in which I planned subsequent projects.  And the point about the article, really, is that there is a gendered dimension to this, and that, in my experience in the clergymen\rquote s wives study, and in the play group study, \'85
 women with very different sorts
 of backgrounds, that I had, nonetheless, found that it was really quite easy to get them into an interview situation where they were revealing some quite private things, largely because one was tapping into some kind of learned, or natural sympathy betwe
en women \'85 It\rquote s been wildly misquoted to say that Janet Finch says that men can\rquote t interview women.  And I don\rquote t think I quite said that!  But \'85
 but that is not the point, actually.  The point is something rather deeper than that, about \'85 in a society which is quite divided on gender lines, in terms of people\rquote 
s experiences and their assumptions about who you can trust and that kind of thing, that it is a different sort of dynamic when you get a woman interviewing a woman, than when you get a man interviewing a woman.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Do you think it\rquote 
s that the technique that a woman uses in interviewing should be any different?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, I don\rquote 
t.  But I think it means that women in those situations need to be highly sensitised to what it is they\rquote 
re doing, and aware that they are trading on something which is about gender, and not just about their skills as an interviewer.  And, therefore, prepared to have moral positions, if you like, on how far you push people in the interview situation, and how
 you use the material that you\rquote ve got, afterwards.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So, basically, it\rquote 
s that women are more likely to reveal themselves to women, and, therefore, you have the extra ethical obligations? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Yes.  I mean, not necessarily more likely to revea
l themselves, but to reveal different aspects of their lives, or to more readily do that, on the presumption that a woman interviewer will have an immediate inherent understand of what they\rquote 
re talking about.  And it may be that sometimes that means actual facts about their lives get revealed that wouldn\rquote t get revealed to a man.  But I don\rquote t think it\rquote s quite so much that that concerns me, it\rquote 
s more that it takes so little effort to get women to that stage, that there\rquote s a danger of lulling the interviewee into some kind of false sense that this is a confidence between women \'85
 The danger is that the interviewee then forgets what you told them at the beginning, that you\rquote re going to do something with this, you know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I know Anne Oakley argues that you should give something back.  Do you agree with that?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, not really.  I think it\rquote 
s quite difficult to do that.  That was one of the things \'85 that was one of the reasons why I wrote the article.  I was quite influenced by that thought, at the time, and it\rquote s difficult \'85 in a sense, it\rquote 
s difficult to argue against, in principle, or I found it difficult at the time, and yet it didn\rquote t feel quite right and I was struggling a little bit with it.  I\rquote m sure, in that article, I might not have reached a position on
 it, but I did subsequently.  I think that \'85 to say that you give something back, colludes with the idea that it isn\rquote 
t an interview. I think that the moral position that I would adopt is that you must remember yourself, and you must keep reminding the interviewee that this is a research interview, and it\rquote s not the beginning of a friendship, it\rquote 
s not somebody who you might meet on a train, and never have to see again, so you can tell them anything you like.  It\rquote s not a potential counselling situation.  It is
 a research interview, with its own rules and boundaries, and that would be my position now.  I\rquote m not sure that I was as clear about it when I wrote that article. Of course I think it\rquote 
s entirely reasonable to be relaxed about the situation, and I\rquote ve always tried, myself, and tried to, you know, set rules for my own people who have worked with me in interviews, that if you\rquote 
re going to talk about your own family, which is what people are usually interested in, since we\rquote ve been talking to them about their families, try and do it after the tape is switched off, after the end of the interview, you know, so that you don
\rquote t influence what they\rquote re going to tell you.  But, on the other hand, it seems a little bit churlish not to, in a way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what happens if they show themselves in acute distress?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That happened to me at a very early stage in my interview career, in the clergymen
\rquote s wives study.  It was quite an early stage, actually.  At that stage, I really \'85 neither had thought about what to do, nor, p
robably, was in a position to do very much, as a Ph.D. student.  And I simply stayed around, you know, for hours, letting somebody talk to me, in the hope that this, in itself, was going to be helpful to them.  In subsequent projects, it hasn\rquote 
t been such an issue, actually, but I think that\rquote s partly because we\rquote 
ve thought through, at the beginning, questions about how far you push people. I would now, in conducting an interview about anything at all, actually, but certainly about family life, which is what I
 really do, I would stop if I see the signs of somebody becoming distressed, or being very anxious about the line of questioning.  I don\rquote 
t think that it is right for, you know, the greater good, or something or other, of collecting research data, to press people on areas which they find sensitive or distressing.  I think it\rquote s wrong.  I think it\rquote 
s their right, as a citizen, even though they\rquote ve agreed to be interviewed, it\rquote s their absolute right, as a citizen, not to find this a distressing experience.  And I think if one takes any other position than that, then you\rquote 
ve got to prepared to work out, you know, how to pass them on to counsellors or whatever, and I just don\rquote t think that\rquote s the role of the researcher.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Okay.  So I think we\rquote ve reached the point when you start on }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , 1985, I think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Mmm.  Yes.  I mean, that was obviously very much a defining moment in my career, because that was the point at which I, having doing quite a number of things in the previous ten years \'85 I mean, it wasn\rquote 
t necessarily planned this way, but did, in fact, settle down to work on kinship, as what subsequently became the focus of all my work really.  And I did it, I came at that topic from a variety of different angles.  Well, first of all, I knew that I
 wanted to get a larger grant.  I knew that having been successful in the Play Group study, and had good end of grant report feedback from ESRC and so on, that I \'85 the next thing to do was to get a bigger grant.  And I was quite, and by that time I
\rquote d got the confidence to think I could run a bigger project, and that\rquote s the sort of thing I wanted to do.  I came to the topic of family obligations \'85 the most direct route through which I came to that topic, was the work that I\rquote 
d done with Dulcie Groves, on commu
nity care, because we had very complementary skills and backgrounds, if you like, in coming at that, and she had very much been brought up in the orthodox social administration tradition, and knew all about the legislation and that kind of thing.  And we 
w
ere both interested in gender.  I brought to it the eye of the sociologist.  And when we put those things together, I think it was quite powerful work that we were doing at that stage, and it was certainly very influential.  But, having got interested in 
it, what I brought to it was a sociological eye on the informal care study, which, of course, was almost always families. \'85
 Well, family, friends and neighbours is what people talked about there, as being potential informal carers.  But when you scratch the
 surface of the evidence, such evidence that existed at that time, it was very clear that it meant family usually.  So I, increasingly, became interested in that, from the perspective of sociology of family relationships.  And I had kept up an interest in
 family issues.  I\rquote d been an active member of the BSA Family Study Group, which was where I met David Morgan.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh yes.  How did you meet him, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Well, I think I first met him in about, as I was just finishing my Ph.D. actually, and he, you know, I saw him at seminars and so on, from then on, for a few years, but we didn\rquote t \'85 we didn\rquote t get together until 1982, and I didn\rquote 
t really know him very much, very well, before that.  But he was in my life at the time when I was planning the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  study.  And although we\rquote ve never, we\rquote 
ve only ever done one piece of work together, and that was just one article, and he does very different sort of work on families than me, nonetheless, I think it, it probably was an influence in strengthening my 
interest in families as a topic, if you like, because his work was by far and away the best, and the most influential theoretical work on families that was around at that time.  So I was influenced from the theoretical angle, but also, the most direct rou
te through which I came to it was the work that I\rquote d done with Dulcie on community care.  And something was forming in the back of my mind for two or three years, about kinship, and about what was being presumed in \'85
all these policy initiatives about community care.  What was being presumed about the nature of relationships between kin, and what people would, as it were, automatically want to do for each other.  And that\rquote s really where the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  project came from.  And I sat down and thought through, \'93I want to take this further\'94
, and rapidly realised that what I really wanted, would have to do, was quite a broad, and non-policy \'85not with a policy focus, but quite a broad sociological study of kinship, because, really, there was practically nothing then.  There\rquote 
d been nothing since the 1960s really, on \'85
\par 
