\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1773805 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, yes.  Certainly Raymond Firth\rquote s work in North London was enormously influential on the way in which I planned the Family Obligations study.  But Colin Bell\rquote 
s work on middle-class kinship, the Wilmott and Young studies, obviously, were important, although \'85 that was not really a terribl
y big influence, save the kind of assumptions that were around in the policy arena, many of which you could trace back to that work, you know, about the loss of something valuable through urban redevelopment.  So, yes, I think probably the first book was 
certainly the most influential starting point for the Family Obligations work.  And, of course, that was done by anthropologists, and there was always a bit of me that was actually quite interested in anthropology from the time I\rquote 
d worked in Cambridge, and so I was quite keen to follow, you know, some of the lines of thought.  But that is a very good book, because they didn\rquote t just describe what they saw, it is very good conception analysis in that book.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1773805  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Those were the sociological touchstones from which I began originally, but the quest \'85
 I knew that I needed to do something, I needed to produce something on British kinship, contemporary British kinship, in order to be able to address some of the questions that I\rquote d got interested in, that had come from a poli
cy angle.  So the way in which I did it was certainly not just to replicate any other previous study, but to approach the development of the research design, having in mind these questions about \'85
 what is it that can be expected of kin, what the people exp
ect of themselves, and how does this fit in with the foundations of policies that seemed to be developing at that time?  So although it was, by no means, an applied study, there were some pretty applied questions in the back of my mind, driving it.  And I
 
think that blend of sociological work which is, you know, if you take the sort of basic to applied spectrum of research, which is really, in some ways, pretty basic research, but which actually does have, with a few steps of logic, some quite important po
licy implications.  That\rquote s probably been characteristic of most of my work, certainly on kinship.  And probably some of the earlier work as well, now that I come to think of it.  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Could you talk a bit about the methods you used?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Yes.  W
ell, the Family Obligations Survey, as it was done, so the Family Obligations Study had two parts.  It had a survey and a qualitative study.  And I actually can remember, very vividly, the moment when I decided that that had to be.  I originally assumed t
hat it would be based on qualitative interviews, which was what I\rquote d done \'85 all the previous research that I had done had been based on qualitative interviews.  And, at that time, I was very much involved, as I\rquote ve already said, \'85
 I was still writing the book on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Research and Policy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
d finished that when I started planning the Family Obligations Study, and I was very much committed to the importance of qualitative research, both as a sociologist and as somebody who might, potentially, contribute
 to social policy.  And I can remember the moment when I realised, with something of horror, that, actually, the research questions that I was asking, could not be fully answered, unless I had some quantitative data with which to answer them, because some
 of them were the kind of thing that you\rquote re given the answer with quantitative data.  You know, how frequent, how many \'85
 you know, how common, etc., are questions that you can only answer with quantitative data.  And so, you know, with some anxiety that my 
friends would disown me, as it were, I planned a project which was a mixture of a survey and the qualitative interviews.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I\rquote m interested by your saying that some of your friends might disown you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Are you saying the atmosphere was so hostile at that point to qualitative methods?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  No, no.  The reverse, in a way.  I \'85
 most of my friends were qualitative researchers, and heavily committed to promoting the importance of qualitative research.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, I see.  It was the survey side of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
It was the survey side that I thought my friends might disown me, yes, for doing a survey.  But, anyway, there we are!  And, in fact, my friends didn\rquote t disown me, I\rquote m happy to say!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And you were using both those methods at the
 same time?  I mean, that would be unusual, at that point.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Very unusual.  I mean, I don\rquote 
t think I realised quite how innovative it was, until, you know, I was well into it, and I realised that I was doing something that other people were not 
doing.  I mean, I took quite a long time planning it, and went to talk to a lot of different people about it.  The person who was a big influence at the planning stage, was Jackie Burgoyne, who died, tragically, young.  And she had been more prominent in 
family research than I had been, at that stage.  And I remember going to talk to her, several times, about it, and she was one, one person who helped me to concern my feeling that, if you begin \'85
 She was a very talented researcher, and she understood that t
he best research has to begin with the questions, and then the design of the project has to flow properly from the questions.  And not many people that I knew really understood that properly.  And she was the one who confirmed my feeling that this mixture
 of, of survey and qualitative interviews, was really the right thing to do.  And read drafts of the application for me, and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 She was already working on step-families at that stage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
I think she was, yes.  I think that work was quite well underway, as I recall, actually.  Yes.  Yes.  Yes.  And she persuaded me to think about writing a book, at an early stage of the project, which was what }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations and Social Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  turned out
 to be.  In the process of planning the project, which I obviously, I did very thoroughly, I began to see that although there was very little work on British kinship, that had recent empirical base, nonetheless the sort of way in which my sociological thi
n
king was expanding about the topic that I wanted to study, there was, actually, potentially, a huge amount of literature which could be brought to bear on it, if you were really going to do it properly.  And so when I applied for the grant from ESRC, I wr
ote in a year\rquote s sabbatical for myself, as part of the project, which I think I took in 1986/7, I think it was, and I used that year to write }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Family Obligations and Social Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , which was not, which was actually the \'85 the background to the study.  And so I
 was actually working on the survey at that stage, I think, and wrote the book.  But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations and Social Change }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 doesn\rquote t contain any of the data from the study.  It was the, you know, it was the Chapter One, as it were!  (LAUGHS)  But it was, it was a major statement, I think, about the field.  And it\rquote 
s a book that I\rquote m very proud of. So eventually, the research grant had, in essence, three parts.  It had, it had that year\rquote s leave for me to write this book, it had a survey which was conducted by SCP
R, on my behalf, and it had the qualitative interviews, which \'85
 I directed myself, and recruited Jennifer Mason as Research Officer.  And we, basically, did them half and half between the two of us.  And it was a very big project.  I mean, I think I was still a bit na\'ef
ve about research grants at that stage, and I asked for what was then a huge amount of money, it was over \'a3100,000, and in the mid-eighties, you know, that was a very big grant.  But they gave it to me!  And I don\rquote t think I let them down!  Let
\rquote s put it that way!  (LAUGHS)  So it was a wonderful project, and it very much defined my subsequent interest as well, in kinship.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
So, about the interviewing, could you describe what kind of interviewing you were trying to do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 It was an open-ended qualitative type interview, but very carefully planned. \'85
 Jennifer and I worked together on the planning of it as well.  She was quite involved in the intellectual work as well, at that stage.  She wasn\rquote t involved in the survey at all, but she was i
nvolved at that stage.  And we talked through what the content of the interview should be, in such a way that we were as confident as we could be that whichever of us did the interview, we would get comparable data out of it.  And the interview schedule i
s driven partly, obviously, by the kind of descriptive data that we were looking for, about people\rquote s families, about their experiences of giving help to kin, and receiving help from kin, but it\rquote 
s also an interview schedule in which there is a descriptive level, and then there is a conceptual level. \'85 The questions that we asked were at the descriptive level, you know, as you would do with any interview of that sort.  \'93Tell me about \'85
\'94 whatever.  \'93Tell me a bit more about that\'94, kind of questions.  But the wa
y in which we conducted our own thought processes in the interview, was intended to be, and I think, largely was successful, in being something which was driven by the underlying conceptual questions.  Questions like \'93
What type of reciprocity is being pursued here?\'94
  That sort of question, you know, so that we were trying, all the time, in the interview, to anticipate the analysis, and to get people to tell us things that would enable us to distinguish between different types of reciprocity, let\rquote s say.  And
 I think we were able to do that, partly because I had worked on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Obligations and Social Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
, and thought through, really, at quite a level of detail, what the underlying concepts were that you would need to utilise, in order to get answers to the sort of research questions that we wanted.  So we didn\rquote 
t devise the analysis framework, as such, before we\rquote d done the interviews, but we had a very clear idea of what we were looking for.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And when you got onto a point where you had this idea of con
ceptual issues, you would invent questions if necessary?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Correct.  That\rquote s right.  That\rquote s right.  Yeah, exactly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Okay.  And, now, you were saying earlier, off the tape, that some of the interviewees were also in the survey?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes, that\rquote s right. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That\rquote s a very interesting point.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yeah.  Yes.  The two are connected in that way.  The survey was all done in Greater Manchester.  It was sampled, it was 40 wards, sampled from the Greater Manchester, what was then the Greater Manchester administrative area.  And we then \'85
 now, just let me check out the details of this, because I know I was looking at the \'85 appendices, of negotiating family responsibilities.  I think that we had 38 people who had been in the survey, out of a to
tal of 120.  And we selected those, because we had survey data on them, we selected them by characteristics which we thought might be particularly interesting for the qualitative study.  And I actually can\rquote 
t remember, now, the details of how we made that selection, but I think it\rquote 
s in these appendices.  But, [making] the selection, I mean, it was theoretically driven.  We were definitely using the concept of theoretical sampling, at that stage.  So we were definitely not trying to do a sub-sample.  We were 
trying to take ... in fact, we took some of the survey findings and thought about them, and then thought, in the light of these findings, who are the key groups that we need to get more qualitative data on, in order to understand the analysis that\rquote 
s emerging from the survey findings?  And that was how we did it.  And, of course, \'85 we wanted to capture a range of experiences, but we also wanted to \'85 that\rquote 
s right, and we began by selecting people in the following categories.  One group were young adults, and 
the other group was people who had been divorced or separated.  And the reason for that was that we thought that if we started with people in one or other of those groups, and we always had the intention of moving outwards to interview their kin, in some 
cases \'85 if we started with people in those two groups, we would probably be most likely to pick up instances where negotiations about, about obligations between kin, were going on.  Negotiations or re-renegotiations.  Because \'85
 that was an issue that had come out very clearly from the survey, and which, indeed, I\rquote d got very interested in, on the basis of writing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Family Obligations and Social Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  \endash  the negotiated nature of obligation.  And by focusing, initially, on young adults, and on people who had been
 divorced or separated, we, we thought that we would pick up families in which the nature of the negotiation of relationships between kin would be nearer the surface than it might be in families that didn\rquote 
t, that currently were not in a kind of negotiation phase, if you like. So that was why we did that.  And I think I was fairly successful.  We began with \'85 we had actually asked \'85 in the survey everybody had been asked, \'93
Are you willing to be contacted again, to be re-interviewed?\'94  And most people said yes.  So we had that information.  And we had, obviously, some basic information about their profile.  So we, we went back into that, and \'85
 and we ended up with 38 people who fell into one or other of those categories.  And then, as we went along, we decided, having interviewed them once, with some people we just stuck with one interview, used it, but decided that it wasn\rquote 
t going to be, if we went further, it wasn\rquote t going to be rich enough.  With those where we wanted to go further, we did a second interview, and then with most, I think, of those where we\rquote 
d done a second interview, we then asked if we could be passed on to their kin, to interview them.  And so that\rquote s how we built up the total sample of 120.  And we had, I think it was 11 kin groups amongst the 120, if you like.  \tab 
And the methods by which we decided whether we were going to pass on to kin, were quite carefully thought through.  We did a lot of discussion and analysis about the reasons for following through a particular kin group, or not followin
g it through, and we have written an article in which we describe the process of doing that, which is \'85 the article entitled, \'93Decision-taking in the fieldwork process\'94, which, I think, gives a pretty detailed account of how we actually did that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Is it possible just to give some hints about what you say in the article?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 It\rquote s quite a long time since I\rquote 
ve looked at it!  We, yeah, what we say is that we were trying to, all the time, think about the underlying principles of theoretical sampling, and what it is that that means.  So that, for example, \'85
 the principle of searching for negative instances is very important if you\rquote re being serious about theoretical sampling. \'85 That the danger of the kind of methodology which we were using, was that, and I\rquote 
ve seen other people do this, is that because you\rquote re not being driven by some kind of random sampling method, you get seduced into following up people who you think, \'93Oh, that sounds really interesting\'94
.  And there are two dangers there.  One is that you end up with sort of eccentric and exotic examples, if you like, only.  But the more serious danger is that you can\rquote t explain why, there\rquote 
s no intellectual bite to an explanation of why you chose this person rather than somebody else.  And how do you know whether, if you\rquote 
d chosen somebody else, you would get something completely different?  And because I was very interested in the sort of intellectual aspects of qualitative methodology at that time, and as was Jennifer, and we both still are, what we w
ere trying to do was to really think through, \'93On what grounds would you make a selection, if it\rquote s not random?\'94  And issues like the need to search for, you know \'85 So, okay, it\rquote s grounded theory methodology quite \'85
 largely, I think, so the need to think th
rough, at each stage, what, so far, what is our working hypothesis at the moment, about negotiating family responsibilities?  And if we are right, then what sort of people would confirm that we are right?  But even more important, if we have got it wrong,
 what sort of people would show that we\rquote ve got it wrong?  And then you try to follow through the latter as well as the former, so that you\rquote re always \'85
 That sort of principle, I very firmly believe, gives you really a very robust basis for qualitative research, because you can say, \'93Oh, we did our best to disconfirm the hypothesis\'94. I then put it in positivist language, and, \'93
This is how it came out\'94.  So it\rquote s that kind of approach.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Now, another point is that you found yourself interviewing sever
al members of the same family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Could you say something about the advantages and difficulties of that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, the advantages were \'85
 I mean, it was absolutely essential to do something like that, given the underlying 
research questions of the Family Obligations Study. Because the study was all about obligations between kin, and to interview only one person and use them as an informant about obligations, patterns of obligation in which they\rquote 
re involved, even worse, in which other people in their families are involved, is bound to give you only one side of the picture.  And I don\rquote t mean to say it\rquote s necessarily wrong, or distorted, or anything like that, that\rquote 
s an empirical question.  But it clearly is one-sided.  And, therefore, again, \'85
 you know, I think this was very innovative at the time as well, that when I designed the Family Obligation study originally, it was designed to have this feature built in, that there would be more than one side of the story, if you like.  
And so we did that, and it was absolutely essential to do it, at least with some of our interviewees, to be able to get the dynamics of how it\rquote s viewed by different individuals.  And we\rquote 
ve got some instances which you can really only analyse and present as case studies, which are extremely rich, where we\rquote ve got half a dozen members of the same family talking about the same set of circumstances, and how they all viewed it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 It was a group interview, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh no, we interviewed everybody ind
ividually.  Everybody was interviewed individually.  They all knew that the other people were being interviewed... I mean, the way in which we did it, from an ethical point of view, as it were, is that we had, there was always somebody who was a starting 
point, and we asked that person\rquote 
s permission to approach their relatives.  Well, first of all, we asked if they were willing to release the names of their kin.  We asked their permission to approach them.  We then approached them, we told them that their na
me had come from the particular individual, but that that person had made no commitment on their behalf, and that they had to make an independent decision about whether they were happy to be involved in this study.  And, of course, some people said no, so
 we didn\rquote t always have complete kin groups.  But we, for reasons that we\rquote ve talked about, in relation to the ethics of research, we did not push people into saying yes.  We gave them every opportunity to say no, if they wanted to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And did you feel th
at there were problems arising from having these different versions of the same story?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
No, not at all.  I mean, the potential ethical problems I think we dealt with quite straightforwardly.  I mean, we clearly didn\rquote t tell anybody what somebody else had said.  We never did that.  We said that at the beginning to everybody, \'93We
\rquote re not going to pass on what you\rquote ve said, to any of your relatives\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And so also you couldn\rquote 
t then, for instance, publish a case study of a family which was identifiable in any way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Correct.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 It must be very difficult.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 That\rquote s right.  That\rquote 
s quite right.  And we dealt with that mainly by pseudonyms.  And the circumstances of these families was sufficiently common, if you like \'85 I mean, we haven\rquote t got any \'85 very very unusual circumstances in the case studies.  I mean, \'85 I can
\rquote t remember whether we had the opportunity to follow through some like that, but I think we would have rejected that on the grounds that it would have been impossible to use the data.  So it\rquote 
s not likely, having used pseudonyms, that people would recognise themselves.  But we did, in one instance, and it was in an article, actually, not in the book, because of the sensitivity of the circumstances, it was a case study about the care o
f an elderly father, I think it was, where we had data from four or five siblings about it, and there was quite a lot in there about problems in relationships between the parents, and between the parents and the children, that we, in writing that up, we d
id actually, we further changed, we gave alternative pseudonyms, and we also changed some of the details.  I think we changed the gender of some of the siblings or \'85 I can\rquote t remember exactly what we did, but we made changes so that it couldn
\rquote t be recognised.  But, by and large, it wasn\rquote 
t too much of a problem to do that.  I think the really interesting intellectual challenges are about what happens when you put together five parallel accounts of the same circumstance, and get over the hurdle of thinking what you\rquote re doing is \'85
 seeing who\rquote s telling you the most accurate account.  That\rquote s clearly not what you are doing, and I don\rquote t think that, given the kind of sociologist I am, I probably would ever have tried to do that.  But that\rquote 
s what people had tended to think we were doing.  And just look at the way in which the process over time, because you\rquote re almost always hearing about something that was a process over time, viewed retrospectively by five different people \'85
 becomes, it becomes more like a play.  You see the characters in the play acting it out, rather than a narrative read in a novel.  It\rquote s more like a play than a novel, and you have to treat it like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I mean, it\rquote s more difficult to present as well, isn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes, it is more difficult to present.  It is more difficult to present.  And in }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Negotiating Family Responsibilities}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
, which is the book that utilises this data, we rely quite a lot on case study presentation to do that, because although \'85 we use a mixture, we use a mixture of aggreg
ated experiences and case studies, but I think that most of the detail comes in the case studies. \'85 They\rquote re mostly defined conceptually, rather than descriptively.  So case studies which illustrate, particularly well, a concept that we\rquote 
re developing through the argument, but that \'85 in a case study, even in a single case study, you\rquote re giving so much, you have to give so much background information that you can only do one, really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Just going back to the two elements \endash  the survey and the interviews.  N
ow, did you try and make use of the fact that the original group of qualitative interviews came from the survey?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Not very much.  We didn\rquote 
t do much linking back.  We really just used the survey as a sampling frame.  We did, and again, both in that book and in several articles, we\rquote ve actually utilised the data from both together, and tried to analyse \'85 I mean, \'85
 the best analysis that we\rquote ve done from that study does utilise both, because the survey \'85  \tab Perhaps we ought to talk about the survey, because, in some ways, people have said to me it\rquote 
s a survey designed by a qualitative researcher, if you like.  But it was, \'85 the underlying issues wer
e pursued in both, and so something like a concept of negotiation, negotiated responsibilities and obligations, is in both data sets, and so we were able to put them together and look at those kind of issues, and not just simply document experiences.  Sha
ll I say a little bit about the survey?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes please.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 The purpose of the survey was not to find, not \'85
 I did collect a small, a relatively small amount of data on people\rquote s experiences of being involved in mutual aid of one sort or another, with
 their kin.  But that was not the main point of the survey.  The main point of the survey was to, it was what would be called, in survey parlance, an attitudinal survey.  It was about beliefs and values, \'85
 those underlying issues concerning obligations within families.  However, partly because I am, basically, a qualitative researcher, \'85
 I was very dissatisfied with the type of questions which I saw being used in other surveys, which tried to get at beliefs and values, which were either far too direct, you know, \'93Do you think that somebody should \'85 do X, Y or Z?\'94  Or were \'85
 too crudely hypothetical, if you like \endash  \'93What would you do if \'85?\'94  And the sociologist in me said, \'93If you ask either of those questions, you don\rquote t \'85 what is it that you get if you ask either of those questions?\'94
  And I don\rquote t think that you necessarily get what you\rquote re looking for, if what you\rquote re looking for is some kind of underlying structure values which might, really, bear a relationship to what people do in their own lives. So I had so
me very interesting discussions with SCPR about what I wanted to do, and I think they had some reservations about it.  But the major, the most important parts of the survey were built round vignettes, which is where the article about vignettes comes in.  
T
hey were scenarios, you might call them, which I wrote, and I wrote them in a way which was very closely related to the research questions that I was trying to understand.  And some of the scenarios were quite short.  Some of them were just a different wa
y of asking the question, \'93What would you do if \'85\'94, if you like.  And I did know that, particularly in the United States, this kind of approach had been used.  So instead of saying, \'93
What would you do, Paul, if one of your children came to you and said, you know, \lquote I\rquote ve made a stupid investment and I\rquote ve lost all my money, and they\rquote re going to reclaim my house, and \'85 help!\rquote \'85
Yes! Exactly, yes! `Help!'\'94 you know.  \'93What would you do, Paul?\'94  Instead of asking you that, the question would come in the form, \'93Joe B
loggs is in his fifties, with three grown up children, and, you know, still paying off his mortgage, or whatever.  One day, one of the three comes to him and says this.  What should Joe Bloggs do in these circumstances?\'94
  So it was always sort of third party stuff, if you like, which I believed, and I think I was right, enabled people to distance themselves from their immediate circumstances.  So, you know, if I asked the question, \'93
What would you do, Paul, if one of your children did that?\'94  You would start saying, \'93Oh well, just a minute.  There\rquote s this, and there\rquote s that that I\rquote d have to take into account\'94
, whereas doing it in that sort of way, and distancing it to a third party, minimises that.  I\rquote m not saying that you wouldn\rquote t, because people did, I think, say to the survey interviewers, \'93Well, what about such and such?\'94
 you know.  But you\rquote re more likely to get at the underlying values that people bring to bear on those moral judgements, if you like, by doing it that way.  So some of them were relatively s
hort scenarios like that, and then there were four which were much longer and more complex scenarios.  And they came in the form, in sort of stages, you know, that the first stage, you set out something like that, and then \'85
 and you ask some questions of the interviewee about, \'93What should Joe Bloggs do in those circumstances?\'94  And then you say, \'93Right.  Now I\rquote m going to tell you that, in fact, what Joe Bloggs did was to decide that he couldn\rquote 
t possibly give money to one child without giving money to all the others.  So he decided, at that point, that he had to say to the one who was in difficulties, \'93I\rquote m going to give you \'a35,000\'94 or whatever \'93now.  But I\rquote 
m going to tell you that I\rquote m changing my will so that the other two have got \'a35,000, and you won\rquote t have it then\'94.  And so \'85 and then another set of questions about the interviewee\rquote 
s reaction.  And then perhaps a third change in the circumstances, so at each stage in these more complex vignettes, you revealed a bit more about what the circumstance was, and got people\rquote 
s reaction.  And those four were wonderful.  They really gave us wonderful data.  And I\rquote ve written about each of those.  I think I\rquote 
ve written about each of them separately in articles, actually.  And I wrote an article about utilising that technique in survey research, which was the article, \'93On the Use of Vignettes\'94, which I \'85 I did it because I thought, you know, it was 
\'85 written as a research note in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Sociology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
, not as a full article, but it generated a great deal of interest.  But I think I can see why people say this was a survey designed by a qualitative researcher, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Why, exactly, do you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Well, because it was getting at the sort of data, and at the kind of level, level of data, that you would try to get in in-depth
 interviews, but utilising survey methods to do it, because I needed to know what a random sample of the population thought about this.  This is a value base, against which I\rquote m going to understand the way in which actual real people, whom I\rquote 
m going to do these in-depth interviews with, conduct their lives.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So that remains your model for qualitative research, does it?  You have a \'85
 broader basis of information to relate to, and then you have the in-depth interviews? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I don\rquote t think it has to be done like that.  I wouldn\rquote t say that that
\rquote s a sort of standard model that has to be applied to every project.  Not at all.  But in this particular one, which was about values, was about family obligations, and how there are contemporary family obligations
, and how it works in the context of contemporary kinship.  I \'85
 I knew that there was no broader touchstone for the cultural environment in which individuals were making their decisions, and thought that I needed to create it in the context of this project, given that that was what I was trying to find out about.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Now, before we move on, we introduced Jennifer, without your saying anything about her.  I was wondering whether you could say something about her - what was her background, her personality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  I\rquote 
d be delighted to.  Well, Jennifer is my intellectual soul-mate from that time, from the time when she came to work with me, which was, I think, 1987, and still is, though we\rquote re only doing a very very limited amount of work together now. I
 advertised for a Research Officer on the ESRC project, and she applied.  I can actually remember reading her application.  It\rquote s only happened to me very rarely in my life, and I\rquote 
ve been involved in an awful lot of appointments, one way or another, but it happened on this occasion.  I was reading through the applications of the 20 people who\rquote d applied, and I came to her, and I read her letter of application, and I thought, 
\'93That\rquote s it\'94.  You know, it was just completely in tune with what I was looking for an
d what I wanted.  And, of course, we went through the process of interviewing, we interviewed four people and so on, but there was never any doubt in my mind that if the person turned out to be how the letter was, I was going to appoint her.  And I did.  
And it\rquote 
s been a wonderfully productive relationship, it really has.  As I say, I knew when I read the letter, that she was the person.  And when I turned to the application form, I was very interested in the fact that she was actually a product of two peopl
e whose work I enormously admire, and who \'85 I\rquote m still very closely in touch with.  She\rquote 
d been an undergraduate at Southampton, and had been supervised for her undergraduate dissertation by Graham Allen, who is out of the same stable as me, if you like, and
 was one of the few people who was working on family and kinship at the same time as I was, and often we\rquote d read each other\rquote s articles in draft form, and that kind of thing, and who, I\rquote 
m delighted to say, now works for me at Keele!  I didn\rquote t recruit him, ac
tually, interestingly!  That was not my initiative, but he does.  And so Jennifer had done her undergraduate, had been influenced by him in her undergraduate work, and she had then gone on to Kent to do post-graduate study, where she\rquote 
d been supervised by Ray Pahl.  And she hadn\rquote t quite finished her Ph.D. actually, when she came to work for me, so she did finish it in the early months of working for me, I gave her a bit of time to do that.  So, I mean, intellectually, she was 
\'85 she had come out of the sort of \'85 she\rquote d worked with people who were very much in tune with what I did. But that was not the reason why I appointed her.  It was her own approach to things, which was very very much \'85 and we do \'85
 I mean, we both still think that we can read each other\rquote s minds, intellectually, in a way that neither of us can do with anybody else.  You know, we really do think very similarly.  And that means, of course, that we\rquote re each other\rquote 
s biggest critics.  I mean, we can challenge each other in a way that I\rquote ve never fou
nd quite with anybody else.  And so she came and worked with me, as a Research Officer, on the Family Obligations Study, and then was a co-applicant on the Inheritance Study which was funded from the ESRC, a little after we\rquote 
d finished the Family Obligations study.
