\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  Well, that \'85 that was \'85 It wasn\rquote t a follow-up study to }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
, but it certainly grew out of an interest that developed through the Family Obligations Study.  We had a, we had a question, to a limited extent, in our in-depth interviews for Family Obligations, we quest
ioned, to a limited extent, on inheritance, and we got some data on that.  But we hadn\rquote 
t made it a particular focus.  But in the course of doing the analysis of the Family Obligations work, we became very interested in inheritance.  And I suppose it was a 
very nice thing to do, following on from Family Obligations, for two reasons.  One was that the life course dimension to it, if you like.  Our focus on Family Obligations had been very much \'85
 because of the sort of families we were looking for, we started 
with young adults, or people who had been divorced and separated, and then looked at their families.  Although we did have quite a lot of older people in that study, the focus, I suppose, was the kin groups of people who, themselves, were in young, young 
adult life, or mid adult life.  And \'85 tracking the way in which \'85
 obligations and responsibilities were negotiated in the young adult life scale, by and large.  But we recognised that this continues, and realised that if you actually had put the focus on the end of life, you know, if we\rquote 
d have, instead, chosen to start with elderly people, and do their kin group, then we probably would have found \'85 well \'85 or would we?  Question mark.  Have found that there is a further part of this story, which is about how 
the potential for inheritance, to get drawn back into the negotiations of \'85 other sorts of obligations, and to affect the way in which other obligations get negotiated, particularly around elderly people. Questions like, \'93
Does the fact that somebody expects to be left something by a parent or an uncle or something, mean that they feel a different sort of responsibility to support them in old age, than others do if they don\rquote t think they\rquote 
re going to get left some \'85?\'94  That kind of thing.  Secondly, from a pol
icy angle, this was becoming much more live by the early nineties.  Government was starting to look more actively at equity release schemes and that kind of thing, which were specifically encouraging older people not to have anything to leave, and to util
i
se their assets, particularly housing assets, to support themselves in old age, financially.  And we were interested in what that might do to disrupt patterns of obligation, if there was some sort of follow-through.  And thirdly, the other reason why it w
a
s a nice complement to Family Obligations, was that although we had asked quite a lot of questions about financial support, within the Family Obligations Study, in essence the Family Obligations Study was not about the material aspects of family life, if 
y
ou like.  And I recognised, as a sociologist, that many sociologists would think this is a huge omission, and that, you know, economic relationships, within the household, certainly, had been the core of what recent sociology of the family had been about,
 and that we hadn\rquote 
t really looked at materiality at all.  And so the question of the economic relationships between kin was something that we could look at, by utilising inheritance in that way.  So it was a very nice follow-on, but it was planned to be a study which wasn
\rquote t, wasn\rquote t sort of Part II of Family Obligations, but definitely built on what we had learnt about English kinship.  So it was, it was a study of kinship as much as inheritance.  And the book that we have produced most recently, published in
 2000, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Passing On}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
