\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
You did mention, earlier, that part of your interest in this particular area was from your own family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Did I?  (LAUGHS)  I think that \'85 it is not remotely an a
utobiographical project.  But I think that \'85
 if we go back to the mid-eighties, when I was designing the Family Obligations Study, I think my experience of my own family was important in giving me some confidence to challenge the then common wisdom about c
ontemporary families.  And the then common wisdom about contemporary families, which I am distressed to say, is probably, to some extent, still the common wisdom, so really, in that sense, I failed to make an impact on it, was the story with which we are 
all too familiar, that industrialisation in the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  and 20}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  centuries has \'85
 destroyed the strength, the previous strengths that were there of the wider kin group, and has produced families which, in essence, are coterminous with households, and that the w
ider kin relationships are unimportant.  And in a sense, our family lives are relatively impoverished as a consequence of all these changes.  A view which the Bethnal Green studies were partly responsible for promulgating, in my opinion.  And it was partl
y
, partly my own experience of my own family, not just in the past, but in the present, which gave me the confidence to recognise what I really knew from other sources, that this was wrong, that this could not be true.  And I think, probably, the most gene
ral statement that I could make about what I think has been the importance of my work since the mid-eighties, on the topic of kinship, is that I think I\rquote ve produced the basis for showing, very clearly, that \'85
 that kin relationships remain extremely important in the contemporary world, and that, of course, as social and economic circumstances change, the form which they take changes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
But the idea of negotiating those consequences, is that where that came from, watching that happening, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, I\rquote m sure I was influenced by that.  I\rquote m sure I was.  But that
\rquote s quite sociological.  I mean, the first study, for example, is very, very much about that.  I\rquote m not sure that I use the word \'93negotiation\'94, but the first study, I think it maps English kinsh
ip in a way which I very much recognise, which is, they focus very much on the sort of flexibility and the optional nature of relationships with quite a wide range of kin.  And that\rquote 
s something which I recognised from my own family, and very much accords with what I\rquote ve found in my own research.  But it was more, I would say the influence of my family was more to do with \'85 with feeling that an account which says, \'93
Family relationships have shrunk to the household\'94 is just plain wrong, and that if you ask questions of your friends, you\rquote d find that I wasn\rquote t unusual, you know, in \'85
 feeling that relationships across generations, three or four generations, remained important to me at some level, in practical as well as emotional terms, and that lateral relationshi
ps also, to some extent, were important.  And this was true of anybody I asked the question casually of, you know.  So, clearly, the then conventional sociological account of the family was not right, and I saw it as my mission in life to find out just ho
w wrong it was, and in what ways, and to produce a more accurate account.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about the methods you used for the \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Inheritance study.  Well, there were three parts to that study.  We were trying to 
\'85 like Family Obligations, find out a range of different sorts of things, but all around the sort of core questions of how do families utilise inheritance, as part of \'85
 the ongoing relationship of the family, if you like?  How do they manage the process of transmission?  How does that relate to
 the other kind of obligations and responsibilities that they feel to each other?  It was a good case study in the nineties, because of the spread of home ownership.  We know, from other data, that home ownership has expanded from the mid-sixties about, r
oughly about one-third of homes }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1773805 were owner-occupied, to the mid-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
eighties, roughly about two-thirds owner-occupied.  And this meant that, by definition, a much wider range of people were being drawn in to having something valuable to bequeath.  And so we wer
e interested, first of all, only in ordinary families, as it were.  We didn\rquote 
t attempt to do anything on the wealthy, for whom inheritance would have been an issue for a number of generations.  We were interested in trying to understand how people, who were
 relatively new to the experience of inheritance, were handling it, and what that told you about the family relationship.  And so those were the core questions, and they were reflected in the research design.  And we had three elements to it.  The first e
lement, chronologically, was a study of wills.  And the reason for doing that was that that seemed to be the best source to provide some basic documentation on the question of who gives what to whom.  Again, maybe you\rquote 
re going to come to the conclusion that I do have a view about mixing quantitative and qualitative data, but it seemed to me, again, with the particular research questions that we had, we needed \'85
 of some basic kind of background descriptive data on what was the actual pattern of bequeathing, i
n order to be able to understand what people were telling us about the way in which they managed it in their own family.  And rejected, at quite an early stage, the idea of doing a survey on this.  You couldn\rquote 
t have got at this with survey methods at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 People wouldn\rquote t say?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No, well, I think that it is \'85
 it is very difficult to say.  I mean, I know, from the in-depth interviews, how difficult it is for people to remember what they have received, let alone to tell you what their own bequeathing intentions are, you know.  I\rquote 
d like to ask you, Paul, and I bet you\rquote d find it difficult!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I would!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 There you are
, you see!  So, so we actually went for hard data on what people had actually done when they wrote a will.  And we did that through a sample of 800 wills of people who had died, and when they\rquote ve been through probate they\rquote 
re public documents.  So, so we sampled it through the Public Records Office.  And we, we did it over a 40 year period.  We had four sample years, beginning with 1959.  So, \rquote 59, \rquote 69,\rquote 79, and \rquote 
89.  And the reason for that was that it gave us some opportunity to track whether there had been any change over this period when home ownership was expanding.  The answer, we didn\rquote t pick any up, essentially.  We didn\rquote 
t, in the end.  So the fact that we had four sample years, in the end, didn\rquote t mean very much.  And so we sampled these 800 wills, and we
 produced an analysis framework for all of them, we coded all of them, and the analysis was done on SPSS.  And the main output from that part of the study was the book on wills, which was published by Oxford University Press, in their Socio-Legal Series. 
 And that\rquote s, that\rquote s the only book that I\rquote ve ever written which is a fairly sort of straightforward research monograph, if you like.  I mean, I think it\rquote 
s quite a good book, actually, but it contains a lot of data, and less theories than others.  But in the process of doing that, I mean, I actually wrote the introductory chapter on \'93The Use of Wills as Social Documents\'94
, and so I got interested in the use of documentary data, and that kind of thing.  But that was a fairly straightforward product from that.  We did also use some of the wills data in other things that we wrote, but that\rquote 
s the main output from it.  The in-depth interviews were not connected, there wasn\rquote t an actual connection in terms of individuals, between them and the wills study, that was selected on a completely different basis.  And \'85 and I\rquote 
ll talk about that more in a moment.  We had a third part to this study which was really an exploratory, pilot type study, where we interviewed some solicitors.  I think it was about 25 or 30, in the end. 
 It was never intended to be more than a shot in the dark, but it was important to have a go at it, because \'85 we were trying to find out what people \'85
 patterns of bequeathing, and their bequeathing intentions, would tell us about their understanding of kinship.  And could you extract from people\rquote 
s heads, if you like, the model of my kin group, by finding out who they were going to bequeath to?  It was important to know whether, in asking people questions like that, and even more in looking at what the wills
 data was telling us, whether we had any chance of seeing what is the model of kinship in somebody\rquote 
s head, or whether what we were really seeing was what a solicitor told them, advised them to do, right?  And so we, we interviewed solicitors mainly to try and get some sort of sense of what influence they had on \'85 on people\rquote 
s bequeathing intentions.  And had we found that that seemed highly significant, we probably would have tried to raise money separately to do a more extensive study of that.  But, in fact, we didn\rquote 
t think it was terribly important.  It was, in some respects, but we didn\rquote t do very much to follow that up.  \tab So if I come to the in-depth interviews, we \'85
 adopted a rather similar methodology there to the in-depth interviews in the Family Obligations Study, namely, we started with individuals, and then with some, but not all of them, worked outwards and interviewed kin.  And we \'85 we didn\rquote 
t have a sampling frame to draw people from for this, so we, we pieced together our starting individual, on a 
number of criteria.  I suppose it was a version of quota sampling, if you like.  In fact, it was a version of quota sampling.  And we used our initiative, or the research staff working for us, used their initiative to track down people who fitted our init
ial quota, and we used a mixture of methods \'85  We wanted some people in the sort of young adult age group, and we used the Electoral Registers to pick up, you know, in Electoral Registers, \'85
 new electors are identified as new electors on Electoral Registers
, so we knew we could pick up people who were 18, 19, 20, from that method, so we picked up some from there.  We wanted to go to the other end of the spectrum, we wanted some kin groups where we started with an older person, so we, we got access to a numb
er of residential Homes where we interviewed people, and that kind of thing.  It was a mixture of methods.  But we did it on a quota basis, that we knew we wanted to compose it this way.  \tab 
And we used the same kind of approach for deciding whose kin group to follow through, discussions in the research team this time, because we had Jennifer and myself, and two research staff working on this.  We had a fifth collaborator, Judith Masson, who
\rquote s a Professor of Law at Warwick, who worked with us mainly on the Wil
ls study, and also gave us a wonderful tutorial on the legal aspects of all this, which none of the rest of us knew about!  And so we, we built up, the methodology of building up the study population for the Inheritance in-depth studies, were very similar
 
to Family Obligations, and we ended up with a rather similar pattern.  Eighty-eight interviews, eighty-eight interviewees, most of them interviewed only once, a few interviewed twice.  Some of them in the study as a single individual, some of them as a co
uple, some of them with more than, three or more kin in the study.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And in the previous study, you\rquote d looked at \'85
 was it divorced or step-families?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Yes. We did.  We did.  We did, yes.  But in the process of deciding whose kin to follow through, we did take that as one of our criteria, so we were actually positively seeking out people who\rquote 
d had experience of divorce and remarriage in their families \'85 I mean, \'85 not just because it was inherently interesting, though it is very inherently interestin
g from an inheritance perspective, and lawyers get very excited about that!  Oh yes!  But \'85 but because \'85 we believed that, the same sort of logic as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , we believed that if you select people who have some experience of those circumstances, you will be more likely see, visibly, the kinds of \'85
 or they will be more likely to be able to talk to you about the kind of negotiations that go on about inheritance, in those circumstances, and this will tell you about how they perceive the nature of th
e different kin relationships that they have.  So it wasn\rquote t only because that is important in inheritance terms, in socio-legal terms, but also because it\rquote 
s a vehicle through which you enable people to bring out of their heads, what you want to know, if you like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Fine.  Are you actually actively involved in any research projects at the moment?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, now, that\rquote s an interesting question.  I\rquote 
m just on the point of deciding.  I\rquote m about to go on two weeks\rquote  holiday, and when I come back from it, I\rquote ll tell you the answer to that! \'85
 It would be possible to do some more work on inheritance, the data has more things in it that haven\rquote t been mined yet.  And Jennifer and I have been talking about whether either or both of us want to do that.  I think the a
nswer is probably no.  I think I probably want to move on.  The later stages of the inheritance work have gone very slowly, because in 1995 I came here, to Keele, as Vice-Chancellor.  And whilst I told them, from the very beginning, that I did not wish to
 give up being a researcher, and have not done so, obviously I have to work at a much slower pace than I would if I was, you know, a professor.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Mmm.  Do you actually set aside a period every week, for research?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  No, I can\rquote t, I can\rquote t do a 
period per week.  It has to be more opportunistic than that.  It varies a bit at different times of year, and I do use holidays, to some extent, for that purpose. \'85 So I have continued, but it\rquote 
s gone at a much slower pace.  Meanwhile, Jennifer Mason, who moved to Leeds just before I moved here, and who has been involved in a very successful establishment of an ESRC funded Research Group there, in the Centre for Research on Family Values \'85
 a very very good set-up, where I\rquote m on the Advisory Board, so I keep in touch with what they\rquote re doing too.  She, actually, has had two children since I moved here, so she\rquote s also worked at quite a slow pace.  And she\rquote 
s been doing other things, she\rquote s written a book on methodology, and she\rquote s working with the new Research Centre at Leeds and so on, so we\rquote ve both worked fairly slowly on it.  And I think, probably \'85 I think I\rquote 
d like to move on, and I think she should probably concentrate on the things that she\rquote s doing now.  But we\rquote re \'85 we\rquote re just taking a bit of a pause to decide that.  So I\rquote m now at an interesting stage of deciding what I
\rquote m going to do next, which, of course, has to be something, at least initially, that\rquote s quite modest, given my ability to put aside time for research, and something new.  And I\rquote m going to give that some further thought while I\rquote 
m on holiday.  It will be on kinship and family, it will probably not be on the sort of negotiation of obligations, or anything like that, it will probably be something slightly different from that, but it will be on contemporary kinship.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And looking at the whole of your work up till now, what are you most proud of?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
There are a number of ways in which I could answer that, I think.  I mean, in terms of \'85 the impact \'85 no, in terms of the findings, if you like, what 
contribution have I made to sociology?  I think perhaps what I said a little while ago, about having redefined the terms on which we understand families and kinship, is what I\rquote m, what I think has been my most important contribution.  And I\rquote 
ve done that through a variety of different projects, and \'85
 I think that although the public discourse remains stubbornly focused on the idea of households as being what families are, I think that, in sociology, for the relatively small number of people who are interested
 in family issues, that the influence is very clear there.  If you want me to say what is my most \'85 the product that I\rquote m most proud of, the publication, I would probably have to say the book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Family Obligations and Social Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , because it is, I think, by quite a considerable distance, the most influential thing that I
\rquote ve written.  I\rquote m slightly sad about that because it doesn\rquote t contain any empirical data of my own, and, and I do think of myself as somebody who needs empirical data to think with.  And I don\rquote 
t necessarily think that I would put it ahead of the two books, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Passing On}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , or }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Negotiating Family Responsibilities}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 , in terms of its quality, but it\rquote 
s a different sort of book which is \'85 always going to be read by a much wider range of people, because of it\rquote s nature, it\rquote 
s a more theoretical book.  And so I think I would have to say probably that book is, is my most important piece of work.  I think I\rquote m, in a more general sense, I am most proud of having developed a way of doing sociology on families that does \'85
 link in policy questions with some very basic \'85 fundamental type of work on families.  That style of research I\rquote m proud of, too.
