\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And why did you decide you wanted to make that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Well, the then Vice-Chancellor at Lancaster suggested to me that, that I should consider it.  And I was somewhat surprised.  Well, the rest of the University was even more surprised, because there wasn\rquote 
t a vacancy.  He created a vacancy, as it were!  I had, as well as the other things that we\rquote ve been talking about, I had, during the eighties, become involved in quite a lot of na
tional things, actually.  I think we mentioned the BSA at one point.  But I\rquote d also become involved in journal editing and that kind of thing, the obvious things.  But, in addition to all of that, I\rquote d been, from \'85 probably about 1984 or 
\rquote 85, involved in the CNAA, which, at that time, was the validating, awarding body for degrees in all the then polytechnics.  I think I went on, originally, \'85
 on to the Sociology Panel, they had subject panels at that stage, approving validation programmes in my own disciplina
ry area.  But I rapidly got drawn into a wider range of issues there, and ultimately ended up as a person who was very heavily involved in the institutional level approval of degree awarding powers for polytechnics in just that final period, before the go
v
ernment took an instant decision that all polytechnics would become universities, and would automatically have their own degree awarding powers, there was a period when the CNAA was sort of assessing institutions, to judge whether they were appropriate fo
r this.  And I was much involved in that, and I was really quite \'85
 a relatively inexperienced person to do that, but people seemed to, you know, want me to, and I did.  And so I had gained a level of knowledge about institutional management, if you like, second hand, which was \'85
 would not otherwise have come to me, and I found intellectually very interesting, a few different styles of management.  And I was also being used in Lancaster to do some sort of external type things as well, of a rather similar natu
re.  So I was performing relatively senior roles, outside and inside the University, from quite a young age, in this general field of quality assurance.  And as a result of that, just about, I think, at the point when I was given a Personal Chair, the the
n Vice-Chancellor of Lancaster, Harry Hanham, said, \'93I\rquote m going to tell Stuart Sutherland that he has to have you on his committee\'94, and I didn\rquote 
t know what this committee was at that stage, but it turned out to be the committee which devised the academic audit for the old universities.  So there were all these terribly grand people on, and I was the academic, I won\rquote t say \'93token academic
\'94, because they treated me very well.  So I became involved in sort of national policy-making, in a big way, then, for the old universities, in this quality assurance field.  And then I got on to ESRC, I was appointed to the Council of ESRC, and \'85
 I don\rquote t think anybody else had been on Council at Lancaster.  And that sort of thing.  And so I actually had achieved a sort of national prominence which was noticed.  And Harry Hanham had me in one day and said, \'93Look\'94, you know, \'93
You appear to have the ability and inclination to be involved in university management.  Do you want me to give you an opportunity to try yourself out?  And if you do, I\rquote d welcome the opportunity to work as a Pro-Vice-Chancellor\'94
.  So I thought, obviously I thought about that very carefully, and decided that it would be an interesting thing to do for three years, without necessarily having any definite views a
bout whether I wanted to continue with that.  But it was an opportunity to find out whether I liked doing that sort of thing.  So that\rquote s how it came about.  And it did then lead me here, of course!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  You were saying that you found university adm
inistration intellectually interesting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 What do you mean by that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Well, what I found interesting when I was working with the CNAA was that I had only ever worked in the old university sector, the pre-\rquote 92 university sector.  I\rquote d 
never been exposed to the then polytechnics.  And it made me very aware that the different styles of operation were very different indeed.  And with that went a management style that was completely unfamiliar to me, which was \'85
 a much more top/down kind of management, and perhaps more sort of bureaucratic, if you like.  And I found that quite interesting, It gave me cause to reflect on the strengths and weaknesses of that approach vis-\'e0
-vis the strengths and weaknesses that I was familiar with in the old un
iversity sector, about how you get things done.  Because, after all, we were already into a period where things are very difficult for universities, and the pressure to change and adapt, in order to deal to best effect with changing external circumstances
, there were really great pressures, and \'85 Lancaster, as I\rquote m sure all pre-\rquote 92 universities, was not well geared up to making changes rapidly, or even making \'85
 having the confidence and the creativity to change, do different things, if you like, in order to spot opportunities and that sort of thing.  So I could see that \'85
 that style of operation had its disadvantages as well as its strengths.  I could see the strengths of the other style, but, of course, I had something of a natural gut reaction against the top/down style of management.  So just \'85
 because I was constantly exposed to this through the CNAA work, and then later through the \'85 development of the Academic Audit Unit  \'85 I found that my mind worked as a sociologist about this, if you like, and did, an
d I did find it quite a creative sort of thing to think about really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Did you start writing about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.   No, I\rquote 
ve never done any serious writing or research on this topic, no.  No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Maybe it\rquote s better not to!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Maybe, yes!  Absolutely, yes!  Yes, quite!  Mmm.  Mmm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
And when you started with the CNAA business, did you have any sense of a mission to change things in any way, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  No.  No.  Except that I\rquote ve always believed, instinctively, in external 
\'85 public accountability of what goes on in universities.  I don\rquote 
t think I would have agreed to be involved in the CNAA unless I did believe in that.  But I have always believed in it, long before it was fashionable, or, perhaps, one might say impos
ed on some unwilling parts of the sector.  I think the spending of public money requires, requires it.  We don't have an inalienable right to take taxpayers\rquote  money and not have to justify what we\rquote re doing with it. \'85
 And also, I was very conscious, just as a university teacher, and then by that stage, quite an experienced External Examiner and so on, of the variability of teaching quality, and the poor deal that some students can get, you know?  But whether you
\rquote re talking about supervision of Ph.Ds., or about undergraduate programmes where they don\rquote 
t get feedback on their work in a reasonable time, and that kind of thing, I feel quite passionately about the importance of treating students well, and giving them a good educational experience.  So for all these 
reasons, I was actually interested to be involved in, in developing structures of external accountability.  So I didn\rquote t have a sort of mission to change anything in a specific way, but I certainly wanted to be identified with that, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about your role on ESRC?  Can you say something about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Mmm.  I greatly enjoyed that.  I think I first went on to ESRC as a member of what was then the Research Centres Board, which was rather short-lived actually, but which oversaw the work of th
e Funded Research Centres.  And that was quite interesting, because, as a member of that Board, the Board was newly formed when I went on to it, and Howard Newby came and gave us a pep talk that said \'85
 we were meant to sort out some of the Centres that wer
e not operating to best effect, kind of thing.  And thus it was that various of us were sent out to read the Riot Act to well-known people (LAUGHS), which was quite interesting!  So I think the Centres Board did a reasonably good job, but then it got abso
r
bed within a different structure.  But I was only on that for one year.  I was then appointed to Council, the Council of ESRC, and when I became a Council member, I was asked to take on the chairing of the Research Grants Board.  So my main role, my main 
sort of operational role for ESRC, was to run the Research Grants Board for three and a bit years.  It was \'85
 a thoroughly enjoyable experience, but very demanding.  I took it over at a point not too long after the Grants Board had been formed, and it had be
en formed against quite a lot of hostility from the academic community because, before then, the structure had been that disciplines had their own Boards, and each disciplinary Board had an allocation of money, so that sociology or politics, economics, or
 
whatever it was, always knew that that was their pot of money, and it would go to them.  The structure was changed, I think about 12 months before I took it over, so that the Grants Board dealt with all applications in the responsive mode, across the Soci
al Sciences, and then there was another Board that dealt with the programmes and the things which ESRC was putting some direction into, if you like.  And the Grants Board was seen, at that time, by social scientists, as being something that couldn\rquote 
t possibl
y work properly because, you know, you only had two political scientists and two economists, or whatever, how could they possibly decide on all of this, you know?  And nobody else would know anything about it, and the whole thing would just become a \'85
 individual fiefdom of whoever happened, whichever individual happened to be their disciplinary person on the Board and so on.  And I was very aware of the criticisms that had been levelled at it, and I felt it was my job to make it work. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And how did you get over that problem?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, by usual leading by example, I think! \'85
 I did two things.  One was that I established the principle that everybody was supposed to read \'85 not necessarily every application, but a wide range of applications outside the
ir own field, and I expected people to comment on applications outside their own field.  And the symbolism of this was that I, personally, read every application for every round, and I always had a comment to make on every application.  Now, since there a
re two hundred and odd every round, it was a really big job, but I think it was important in demonstrating that this is how we do it, and expecting \'85 I\rquote 
m not going to allow a situation where the two political scientists tell the rest of us which ones to acc
ept, because that would actually have made the whole thing impossible to do, anyway, because everybody would have escalated their grading, to try and get their discipline with more \'85
.  So there was that.  The other thing that I did, which made it possible,
 I think, for people to comment on it, was that I tried, very explicitly, to identify what was the sort of common ground issues, or areas where any social scientist ought to be able to comment on a proposal well outside their own normal field.  And this t
e
nded to be methodology, research design and methodology.  So, what I personally looked at, obviously, in applications from disciplines, will be on my own knowledge, but also what I encouraged discussion of.  So that, on many occasions, we had highly rated
 \'85 projects that were initially highly rated when they came to the Board, from referees and from the Board members, which I said, \'93No\'94, you know, \'93This is a \'85\'94 either because they hadn\rquote 
t told us what the methodology is, or because the methodology doesn\rquote t fit the research question, it\rquote s the wrong methodology, or because the design of it just doesn\rquote t follow through.  You know, they say this is what they\rquote 
re interested in, they\rquote re doing that, it doesn\rquote t fit together, and so on.  And in a sense, encouraging signs
 of professionalism across the social sciences, which gave us a common language, in order to ensure that the Board operated as a single Board, and not as a series of disciplinary cabals.  And I\rquote 
m very proud of that.  I think it did work.  I know it worked, actually.  And there hasn\rquote t been \'85 I mean, those criticisms have gone away, more or less, now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
So with the peer references, what was your attitude if you got one very unfavourable one, and the rest were very favourable?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I think it\rquote s like \'85 
a number of other things.  I mean, the same problem when I was editing a journal, when I was editing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Sociology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 .  The same problem when you\rquote re doing internal promotions.  It\rquote s the same problem.  You always have to ask yourself whether there\rquote s something that underlies this.  I mean, it\rquote 
s relatively easy if you\rquote ve got five very favourable ones, and one not very favourable.  It would be unusual to get that situation, and not to be able to explain \'85 [why] was that unfavourable?  Whether it was somebody had misun
derstood it, that can happen.  You can see a referee\rquote s misunderstood what the project\rquote s about.  You get, when you see hundreds of these a year, you get to smell out, very easily, the ones where it\rquote 
s some sort of self-interest, you know.  \'93Don\rquote t want this person to do this project because that\rquote s really my territory\'94, kind of thing!  So there were \'85 there were things like that. \'85
 Certainly the systems that we operated there, and I hope that I\rquote ve operated in other circumstances, are reasonably good at taking \'85
 I mean, you have to take the referees comments extremely seriously, and that is the basis, really, of your decision-making, in many ways.  But, at the same time, the decision is made by the Board, and the Board has to exercise judgement about what the re
ferees are telling them.  And so \'85 well, there were certainly a number of occasions on which we had six very good, or however many, referees that said, \'93This is a wonderful project.  Fund it\'94, where we didn\rquote 
t fund it.  And the most common, the most common reason for that is that the referee\rquote s comments had not picked up the evident weaknesses in research design, or something like that, and they\rquote d just \'85 often referees would concentrate on, 
\'93This is a wonderfully interesting topic.  It must be funded\'94.  And they\rquote re telling you to fund the topic.  Well, what you\rquote re asking them to tell you is, \'93Is this project a high quality project on this topic?\'94
, and quite a lot of referees don\rquote t tell you the answer to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And what about the relationship between acade
mic interests and wider policies?  How did you solve that one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
I was in the small group of ESRC Council members that had two weekends away, which were defining moments for ESRC, in which we devised what turned out to be the thematic approach.  I was appointed to the Council just around the time, I can\rquote 
t remember whether it was just before, or just after, around the time that the White Paper, the \rquote 93 White Paper on Science and Technology came out, \'93Realising Our Potential\'94, it was called.  And at tha
t time, all the Research Councils were given new Royal Charters, which re-specified what they were meant to do, and put the emphasis on the two areas of wealth creation and quality of life as being the purpose of it, and so on.  So you couldn\rquote 
t avoid, there was no way of avoiding it.  There was no way of saying, \'93Go away!  We don\rquote t want to do this\'94
.  And ESRC had to work out how it was going to handle this.  Ron Amman was just appointed new as the Chief Executive, and Bruce Smith was a relatively new Chair.
  And we did it.  You know, we went away for two weekends, and we hammered it out, a small group of us, and we came up with a model which, I think, to some extent, sometimes I look at what\rquote s happened subsequently, and thought, \'93
It should be a bit more subtle than that\'94, \'93It was intended to be a bit more subtle than that\'94
, but, nonetheless, I think it has been successful: on many criteria, a successful way of squaring the circle between wanting to make sure that the Research Council goes on supporting the highest quality work that\rquote 
s possible, and goes on being open to supporting, and encouraging of, work that\rquote s completely new and different, and nobody\rquote s thought of before, but really looks very much as if it might become the leading edge.  Squaring the circle 
between that and the need to demonstrate public accountability again, that the work that\rquote 
s being funded is something that will contribute to either wealth creation or the quality of life, in some indirect way in most cases, but, nonetheless, is important.  And we did that, by those themes, because \'85
 the logic was that you had to have some principles of selection.  You can\rquote t fund everything.  That\rquote s true, anyway.  Research Councils have always had principles of selection.  And what we needed to do was to mak
e those principles of selection more transparent and link them to big public questions, if you like.  So that it\rquote s entirely possible to fund basic research that doesn\rquote 
t have much obvious policy implications, on those questions, just as you can fund something that\rquote s very policy-oriented, but they are around big basic questions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
I was also wondering, on this question of how decisions are made on funding, how do you see the role of the lay people in that?  When you were Chairman of the Board, did the Council actually review all these decisions? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 No.  Not \'85not individual fun
ding decisions.  The Council was setting the strategic direction, and when it came to the, the side of the work that I was not directly involved in, which was the Programmes and Centres, and that kind of thing, what is now the Priorities Board work, obvio
u
sly Council members were invited to express views about the future possible Centres, review the pattern of things that were being funded under the existing regime, and comment on whether it looked as if it was the kind of thing we should be doing, given w
hat the themes were, and so on, but not making individual decisions on what should get funded, that was always delegated.  The Grants Board\rquote s decisions never got discussed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Okay.  So \'85 I think it\rquote s overlapping, isn\rquote t it, that you came here in 
\rquote 95?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Uh-huh.  That\rquote 
s right.  It does overlap.  Yes, it does.  I was still Chairing the Grants Board when I came here.  I was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So can you tell me how you became Vice-Chancellor?
