\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1773805 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 How long have you got!  (LAUGHS)  Well, I\rquote ve explained how I came to be Pro-Vice-Chancellor at Lancaster, and that was quite, quite directly \'85
 done to give me an opportunity to decide whether I would like to go further.  I didn\rquote t expect to be offered a Vice-Chancellorship after only three years as a Pro-Vice-Chancellor.  \'85
 I saw it as one possible way forward.  I quite enjoyed my time as a Pro-Vice-Chancellor, though there were some difficult aspects to it, maybe that\rquote s inevitable.  But I enjoyed enough of it to think that if \'85
 if I could be appointed to a university w
here I felt that I was the right person, if the fit was right, you know, the chemistry was right, that I was the person who, at that point in time, could do something for that university, and that it was a university that was likely to respond positively 
t
o the kind of way in which I would be a Vice-Chancellor, then I would be quite interested in doing it.  But I never saw it as something that was an ambition that I wanted to fulfil, as a top priority, and would not have wanted to become a Vice-Chancellor 
in any university that would have me, just because I wanted to be a Vice-Chancellor, kind of thing.  I was very much looking for fit.  And \'85
 would have been quite comfortable with alternative futures, if you like.  Had I not become a Vice-Chancellor, I prob
ably would have stayed a Pro-Vice-Chancellor for a second term of office, or something like that, at Lancaster.  And then what I would have done would have been to focus more heavily on my research, and I probably would have done something like try to get
 a Research Centre or something like that, you know.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1773805   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I didn\rquote 
t actually apply for it, but I was approached in the search process, as it were.  Didn\rquote t know much about the University at all before that.  I\rquote d only ever been here once before, to examine a Ph.D. some years previously.  I hadn\rquote 
t had much to do with it, apart from that.  But came down, met David Vincent, who was actually leading the search process, talked about it, and decided that I would throw my hat in the ring, as it were, and got appointed.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1661543 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 So what attracted you to it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
It was, I think the thing that attracted me above everything else, once I got to know it, is that it seemed to me to be a university, and thus it proved, which has a stronger and more coherent educational philosoph
y than any other, which derives from its origins, which, obviously, has not been preserved in aspic, it has developed, but, nonetheless, is one that I can very much identify with.  And it\rquote 
s a philosophy about the importance of intellectual breadth, and the ability to move between disciplines, and that\rquote 
s expressed in the way in which, particularly, the undergraduate programme is structured.  So that was the most important thing.  And I thought \'93This is a very interesting place that has this view of life\'94, if
 you like.  I was also attracted by the fact that it had a significant and growing presence in health, because one of the things that we haven\rquote 
t talked about is that, in the early nineties, I was, I was made a member of the Regional Health Authority, in th
e North-West, and that was my first contact with anything to do with the Health Service, but I rapidly recognised the importance of the interplay between the Health Service and universities, and recognised that that was a growth area and so on.  Did actua
l
ly, probably my most important legacy as a Pro-Vice-Chancellor at Lancaster, was to get Lancaster connected into the research agenda of the Health Authority, and a very large Regional Grant came to Lancaster for five years, as a consequence of that.  And 
the fact that Keele was into the health arena, and wanting to grow in that arena, was another attraction.  So I think those are probably the things that I would, I would highlight.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And did you have a sense of what you wanted to change?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Yes.  
I did, as one must do, quite a lot of homework, before I actually got appointed.  And as a result of that, I thought that there were three areas which I would make the things that I wanted to focus on, at least initially, when I came here.  And I have don
e so.  And I have made some progress in all of them, though not necessarily, you know, completed the task.  Naturally, other things arise, but I think I more or less got them right.  \tab 
And they were, not necessarily in any order of importance, to focus research on a relatively small number of things that we can do well, for a small university that\rquote s the only rational thing to do, and not to try to do too much.  That doesn\rquote 
t necessarily mean that \'85 there are some Departments that don\rquote t do research, in fact, that\rquote 
s not so, but within a discipline not to try to spread yourself too thinly, and to think imaginatively about how you mount a teaching programme that\rquote s broadly based, whilst actually concentrating your research.  So that\rquote 
s one thing, our research focus.  The second thing was post-graduate work.  I was very struck by the fact that Keele had a very large proportion of post-graduate students, it\rquote 
s currently about 25 per cent, I think.  And that ought to have meant that it felt like a different sort of univer
sity than it did.  In my early contact with it, you know, post-graduates were invisible, and the whole University seemed organised on the basis of the undergraduate needs and timetable and everything.  So, finding a better focus for post-graduate work, ra
i
sing the profile of post-graduate work, turning the University in a direction where it was as geared to post-graduate needs as to undergraduate needs, was another, was the second one.  And the third one was to do with the region, and I think this has prob
ably been the most important, and probably the most successful of the three.  Keele has a history of not being connected with its locality.  I think that was typical of universities of this generation, and that\rquote s dangerous, that\rquote 
s deeply dangerous, in my op
inion, in the present climate.  And so I put a lot of effort, personally, in getting involved in things in the immediate locality, and in the wider region, and getting the University involved in them, and so on.  So those are the three things.  And I thin
k I more or less got them right, actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And do you think being a sociologist is a help as a Vice-Chancellor?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 I\rquote 
ve thought about this quite a lot, actually, because, of course, there are a growing number of us who are.  And I don\rquote t \'85 I don\rquote t think that I can recall, hardly ever, having sort of thought self-consciously, \'93
Mmm, this is interesting, sociologically\'94, but, certainly not having thought, you know, \'93Well, my sociological understanding tells me that I ought to do something this way\'94. 
 But I do think that the, the mind set that you have, as a sociologist, as a social scientist, perhaps, more generally \'85
 No, as a sociologist, the mind set that you have is one in which you approach the whole of your life, I think, probably, and that does influence, I think, the way \'85
 that I think about the University.  So, for example, to give you an example, I know that \'85 I don\rquote t take things at face value, if you like, and if somebody is complaining about something specific, and making my life a bit diffi
cult over it, I think I do, naturally, try to locate them, in their social circumstances, within the University environment, and \'85 think about what it is about those circumstances that\rquote 
s producing this, and not just see it as an awkward individual only.  So it\rquote 
s that kind of thing.  And thinking about the nature of the organisation, and the way in which, without implying a sort of totally functionless model, but the way in which, you know, if you, if you kind of poke it there, something happens over there, it
\rquote s \'85 you know, the organisation has a dynamic of its own, which, I think, a sociological understanding helps quite a lot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 What are the biggest pleasures and pains of doing this kind of work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, the biggest pleasures are successes, of course.  And it\rquote 
s quite nice to be able to point to specific successes, and if they\rquote re important, it matters.  And the biggest success that I\rquote ve had since I came here, was that we were successful in bidding for a new Medical School, and that\rquote 
s probably about the biggest thing that I could possibly have done, so it probably will end up as being my main achievement, however long I stay here.  And things like that are very good, because you\rquote re actually doing all so
rts of things, not only for the University, but also for the locality and so on.  So making a difference in that kind of way is \'85 very very satisfying, because when you\rquote re making a difference successfully, you\rquote 
re doing quite big things.  I think that there are more kind of day-to-day satisfactions about \'85
 getting an organisation working more smoothly, more effectively, more comfortable with itself, or whatever the particular issue is, being able to put individuals into a situation where they can flourish, e
ven though, sometimes, they might not have thought of putting themselves there.  That kind of thing is very rewarding.  The pains are \'85
 almost all of it comes down to money, actually.  You know, the university sector, as a whole, is in a much tighter situa
tion than government will give credit for.  And Keele is a small university, so you have less buffers to withstand it, and one that has never had any reserves, as it were.  So we\rquote 
re always managing at the margins, and that means that there are very specific anxieties associated with that, naturally.  And also \'85 you always don\rquote 
t have quite what you want to be able to invest in new things, and to make new things happen, and that kind of thing.  So \'85 so there\rquote s some quite big frustrations there, which \'85 you know, I mean, if they ever outweighed the pleasures, I
\rquote d go, because I\rquote m not the sort of person who would just stick with it because, you know, my self-esteem requires me to be a Vice-Chancellor, or anything like that.  And so, the specific issues change a b
it, but I think those are the underlying ones probably.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
Earlier your research was very related to Feminism.  Do you think being a Vice-Chancellor is, is related to the Women\rquote s Movement in any way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Well, from that point of view it\rquote s a very lonely position.  It\rquote 
s a fairly lonely position anyway, actually.   I am deeply frustrated about the lack of movement in the number of women Vice-Chancellors that we have.  I have, for the past three or four years, been the only woman Vice-Chancellor in the pre-\rquote 
92 university sector, and that\rquote s a disgrace.  It\rquote s a complete disgrace to the system.  It cannot possibly be that there are only, that, you know, I\rquote m the only person capable of doing this.  I\rquote 
m delighted to say that there are two more joining up from 
this autumn onwards.  But it still feels a bit like, you know, one pace forward and three paces back.  Until the two new people join us this autumn, there have been only five women Vice-Chancellors out of 110, or something, and the other four are in the f
ormer polytechnic sector. That means that I\rquote 
m very very conscious, it is an extra pressure on me, without any doubt, that anything that I do, any mistakes that I make, and everybody makes mistakes, you try to minimise the number that you make, but you can\rquote t pretend that you don\rquote 
t make any.  Any mistake that I make is, potentially, going to be seen as something that has gone wrong }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 because}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308  I\rquote m a woman.  \'93That\rquote s what you expect from a woman\'94, and, therefore, has considerable implications for other women who mig
ht potentially become Vice-Chancellors.  I may be over-dramatising this a bit, because there are not that many mistakes that get widely, you know, publicised, one hopes!  But, but nonetheless, it really is, and I think that it\rquote 
s not good for the system to have that happening.  It really isn\rquote t.  It just needs to be \'85 it needs to be no big deal to have women as Vice-Chancellors.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And are you a role model for younger women?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh, I think I feel a huge responsibility to do that, yes.  Not particular
ly self-consciously, I think.  I\rquote ve always enjoyed encouraging younger people\rquote s careers, and it comes very naturally.  And I \'85 I\rquote m happy to play that role directly, wherever I can.  It is, of course it\rquote 
s a very common experience for women, in any leadership position, that you have very high expectations when you\rquote 
re appointed, other women have high expectations, that you will be able to change things.  And, of course, that almost always ends up in disappointment, because you never can change things as quickl
y as they would like, and that you might like yourself.  So I\rquote 
m always conscious of that blend of positive role model and people being disappointed in me.  I think it is part of being in this sort of position.  But, yeah, I am, I have now, recently, taken 
on a new role, for the sector as a whole, in chairing the Steering Committee for the Equality Challenge, which is raising the profile of Equal Opportunities issues quite considerably, across the sector.  And I\rquote 
m chairing this Steering Group, which is seeing the whole thing through.  And that\rquote s, at the moment, my most visible commitment to try to do something about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 And just as brief last question: what do you do to relax?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 What do I do to relax?  Well, \'85 holidays are important to me.  I alw
ays know when the next holiday is going to be.  I learnt that at a very early stage in my life, that I\rquote m quite capable of working flat-out, for longish periods of time, but if I don\rquote t know when the next break is coming, I don\rquote 
t perform to my best effect.  So I always have a next holiday scheduled, even if it\rquote s only a weekend, or a long weekend, and I always stick to that.  I don\rquote t sort of give up holidays because I think I can\rquote t get round to going, I
\rquote ve got too much work.  I\rquote m quite good at relaxing, quite good at switching off.  Switching off does sometimes include taking some research with me, but then that\rquote s a pleasure!  Certainly different from what I normally do.  So that
\rquote s important.  Other than that \'85 David and I are both very interested in the theatre, and we do go to the theatre regularly, and \'85
 things like that, regular concert series in the winter, try to do things like that, which have to be pre-planned, so that you stick to it, and not leave things to chance, I guess.  So cultural interests, visual art, \'85
 we tend to try and see most of the major exhibitions that we\rquote re interested in, one way or another, weekends in London, that kind of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 
And just one tiny question.  What would you say have been the worst and the best things in your life, so far?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Janet:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1661543\charrsid8421308 Oh!  That\rquote s impossible!  (LAUGHS)  I don\rquote t think \'85 I don\rquote 
t know if I can answer that, actually!  Not because I don\rquote t want to, but I don\rquote t know whether I know what the answer is!  Oh!  I think if I tried to answer that, I\rquote d come out with something silly, actually, because \'85 I can\rquote 
t really think of that, the answer to that, actually.
\par 
